OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: Purkinje cell degeneration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: Purkinje cell degeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: by 7 months of age without death of other neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: Purkinje cell degeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: develop extensive axonal dystrophy of cerebellar Purkinje cells at 4-5 weeks of age, with signs of degeneration detected by P15 widespread hypertrophy of Purkinje cell axons at 5 weeks of age and these axons display many abnormal focal swellings forming varicosities or large spheroids, characteristic hallmarks of degenerating axons extensive loss of Purkinje cells is seen at 4 months of age but not at 7 weeks of age loss is progressive with many cells degenerated, particularly in the rostral region in 10 month old mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: Purkinje cell degeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: severe loss of Purkinje cells by 16 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: Purkinje cell degeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: many of the Purkinje cells are lost from the cerebellar cortex in 2 year old mutant mice Purkinje cell function (prolonged inhibition of simple spike frequency) is also impaired in these 2 year old mutants

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: Purkinje cell degeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Purkinje cells of the cerebellar cortex exhibit crippled dendritic trees with narrower profiles and irregular swellings; however, no sulfatide storage is detected in these cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: Purkinje cell degeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: by 2 years of age, fewer Purkinje cells are found, and the number of radial extensions of cerebellar Bergmann glia into the molecular layer of the cerebellum is significantly decreased

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: Purkinje cell degeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after 70 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mature B cells in aged mice lack CD23 expression unlike in wild-type mice indicating an age-dependent loss of part of the normal B cell differentiation program

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in bone marrow of recipients, numbers of Foxp1-null pro-B, pre-B and B220<sup>hi</sup> B cells are lower than Foxp1 heterozygous B cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced B200 expression on peripheral blood B cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impaired in a cell-intrinsic manner not rescued by provision of a prearranged BCR

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: B cells undergo D-J<sub>H</sub> rearrangement at levels 10-50-fold lower than wild-type and 2-3-fold lower than Xrcc5<sup>tm1Dbr</sup> homozygotes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: both D-J and V-DJ rearrangements are detectable in mutant bone marrow DNA but are greatly reduced (more than 100-fold) in level compared to controls, so functional Ig rearrangements can be generated at low frequency

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell differentiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: B cell development is impaired and results in increased numbers of large pre-B cells compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: partial block

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: B cells show partial resistance to apoptotic stimuli, including cytokine withdrawal and BCR crosslinking, but are just as sensitive to VP16 and gamma-irradiation induced cell death as wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: B cells accumulate endosomal vacuoles containing Cd74 N terminal fragment compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: V(D)J and DJ rearrangement is impaired in Foxp1-deficient pro-B cells in recipient mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: defect in IgH chain gene expression in pre-pro-B cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: pre-B cells exhibit decreased viability compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: immature and transitional B cells exhibit a 3-fold increase in cell death compared with control cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: progression through the cell cycle (G0 to G1 and S to G2/M) in B cells is delayed compared to in wild-type cells B cells exhibit increased viability compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: progression through the cell cycle (G0 to G1 and S to G2/M) in B cells is delayed compared to in wild-type cells B cells exhibit increased viability compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: naive B cells express 50% - 90% less H-2K<sup>b</sup> and have decreased H-2D<sup>b</sup> expression

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: addition of Tnfsf13b (BAFF) to the in vitro B cell cultures does not elevate survival of B cells for the first 12 hours but provides benefits when present for 24 hours or longer

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: pre-BCR-mediated functions are impaired compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal B cell physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD4-positive, alpha beta T cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: stimulated CD4+ T cells are larger than similarly treated wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD4-positive, alpha beta T cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: total numbers of CD4+ single positive thymocytes decrease over time

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell number

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: effector CD4+ T cells from 8-10 week old mutants exhibit greater resistance to antigen induced cell death (AICD) restimulation of activated CD4+ T cells in the presence of activated B cells results in an increase in B cell survival, suggesting that CD4+ T cells cannot eliminate activated B cells efficiently

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: CD4+ T cells are less responsive to IL-7 and exhibit a reduced survival compared to CD4+ T cells from IL-7-treated Cops8<sup>tm1Nwe</sup> Tg(CD4-cre)1Cwi heterozygotes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: pronounced defects in TCR-initiated proliferation and production of Ifng, IL-4 and IL-2 upon stimulation with anti-CD3 or anti-CD3 plus anti-CD28 some responses are partially corrected by addition of exogenous IL-2, but IL-4 production block is not relieved cells exhibit impaired IL-4 and IL-13 production upon stimulation with anti-CD3, anti-CD3 and anti-CD28 or PMA plus ionomycin

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD8-positive, alpha beta T cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CD8-positive, alpha-beta cytotoxic T cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CNS glial cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CNS glial cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: glial fibers in cortical sections between E18.5 and P14 do not develop glial endfeet but terminate at varying positions within the marginal zone close to the meningeal layer glial endfeet are absent at the surface of the cerebellum and within the folia, glial fibers occasionally invade the granule cell layer but do not form expanded endfeet at any age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CNS synaptic transmission
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit a significant cortical excitation and inhibition imbalance

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CNS synaptic transmission

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CNS synaptic transmission
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 10% reduction in vesicular release probability (ratio of excitatory postsynaptic current [EPSC] and readily releasable pool [RRP] charge) in cultured autaptic hippocampal glutamatergic neurons 21% reduction in vesicular release probability (ratio of excitatory postsynaptic current [EPSC] and readily releasable pool [RRP] charge) at low external Ca2+ concentrations in cultured autaptic hippocampal glutamatergic neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CNS synaptic transmission

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal CNS synaptic transmission

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Cajal-Retzius cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal DNA repair

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal DNA repair

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal NK cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: NK cells exhibit partially reduced conjugation with RMA-S cells compared with wild-type cells decreased killing of hematopoietic cells RMA-S and YAC-1 cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal NMDA-mediated synaptic currents
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: NMDAR to AMPA receptor fEPSP ratio is significantly higher in null neurons

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal Paneth cell granules before and after infection

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Purkinje cell axon collaterals form misshapen boutons that are often displaced

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell dendrite morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: focal swellings beginning at 6 weeks and becoming more widespread with age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell dendrite morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: focal swellings beginning at 6 weeks and becoming more widespread with age

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: distal spine density is 143% of controls spine lengths are greater

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell dendrite morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell migration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell migration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced microtubule network

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Purkinje cells of adult mutant mice revealed a hyperspiny phenotype distinguished by additional perisomatic dendrites and multiple perisomatic and proximal dendritic spines not observed in age-matched controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduction of ER-mitochondria contacts in the somata

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P0, cerebellar Purkinje cell (PC) multivesicular bodies (MVBs) have 24% fewer intraluminal vesicles (ILVs) per MVB than controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: large autofluorescent structures in Purkinje cells, often clustered, and surrounded by membranes that stain positive for the lysosomal marker protein Lamp1 vesicular structure contents stain positive p62 (a receptor for cargo destined to be degraded by autophagy), suggesting that autofluorescent deposits represent undegraded autolysosomal material ultrastructural analysis of Purkinje cells shows clusters of vesicular structures filled with autophagic material as well as abnormally shaped electron-dense lipofuscin-like deposits, while only a few lipofuscin particles are found in wild-type controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Purkinje cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 10-12 months, the antler-like shape of the normal Purkinje cell dendritic tree is missing, whereas the somata of Purkinje cells are of normal morphology and number, and no storage of sulfatide is found

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal S-shaped body morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E14.5, S-shaped bodies are absent

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ST segment

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Schwann cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Schwann cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Schwann cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in myocardium and gut incomplete Schwann cell covering of small and thick bundles noted

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Schwann cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after P7, the number of Schwann cell nuclei increases

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Sertoli cell barrier function
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: biotin tracer permeates into seminiferous tubules indicating disrupted blood-testis barrier

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Sertoli cell barrier morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal Sertoli cell morphology and blood-testis barrier structure with large irregular cavities is seen in the seminiferous epithelium basal tight junction proteins (N-cadherin and beta-catenin) and ectoplasmic specialization protein (ZO-1) are found beyond the basement membrane of seminiferous tubules and diffusely present at the blood-testis barrier, extending towards the lumen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Sertoli cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: infertile males display extensive vacuolization of Sertoli cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Sertoli cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: most adult seminiferous tubules exhibit signs of Sertoli cell vacuolization

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Sertoli cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cytoskeleton of Sertoli cells shows disruption of microtubular arrangement and actin organization length of vimentin filaments in Sertoli cells in seminiferous tubules is shorter

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Sertoli cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 8 months of age, Sertoli cells show accumulation of intracellular sulfogalactosylglycerolipid (SGG) and abnormal morphology such as dislocalization of the nucleus and smaller sizes with fewer cellular processes some Sertoli cells have numerous lysosomes with irregular shapes and heterogeneous content or enlarged spherical structures; lipid droplets are abundant esp. at stages I-VII of the spermatogenic cycle in some tubules, lysosomes of Sertoli cells are quite large, more or less spherical and numerous, indicating a lysosomal storage disorder

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: draining lymph node cells from KLH immunized mutants proliferate at a lower rate than wild-type cells and show a reduction in IL-2 and TH1-type cytokine production

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced accumulation of activated CD69+ and CD44<sup>high</sup> T-cells in aortic tissue after angiotensin II treatment in AdCre-treated mice relative to control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: purified T cells fail to secrete IL-2 in response to T cell receptor activation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: anti-CD3 antibody stimulated double positive T cell apoptosis is reduced in the thymus; however T and B cell development and B cell activation are normal after 36 hours of culture with anti-CD3 antibody homozygous T cells produce very little IL2, IL4 or IFNG unlike wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: T cell hyperactivity evidenced by increased cytokine production and higher spontaneous NF-kappaB activity

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: nearly all T cells exhibit an activated phenotype in the absence of an overt antigen challenge unlike in wild-type mice following stimulation with anti-CD3 plus anti-CD28 antibodies or phorbol 12-myristate 13-acetate plus ionomycin, a higher percentage of CD4+ T cells produce IL-1 and CD8+ cells produce IL-2 and IFN-gamma compared to in treated wild-type mice T cells acquire the activated phenotype during the double positive to single positive thymocyte transition by a cell-autonomous mechanism

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increase in cellular size following stimulation, an indication of activation, is substantially reduced in T cells compared to in T cells from Cops8<sup>tm1Nwe</sup> Tg(CD4-cre)1Cwi heterozygotes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: CD4 T cells flux less calcium upon TCR stimulation than in controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: T cells from lymph nodes of non-arthritic mice have higher rates of proliferation in response to anti-CD3 treatment than controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: marker analysis indicates  that the enlarged pool of GPI<sup>-</sup> CD8 T cells is less activated than normal T cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell clonal deletion
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: thymocytes are impaired in a late stage of maturation and  show limited clonal deletion to the Mls-1a self-superantigen but not to staphylococcal enterotoxin A

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell clonal deletion
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: injection with the T cell superantigen SEB does not cause clonal deletion of T-cells bearing Vbeta8 TCR chains as it does in wild-type mice inhibition of activation induced cell death by IL-6 is almost three times greater than in wild-type T cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: partial block in the transition from double negative to double positive T cells block appears to be at the DN3 to DN4 transition as a significant proportion of cells fail to down regulate CD25

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: T cell differentiation is impaired the level of recombination signal sequence (RS) joins in mutant thymocyte DNA is substantially reduced compared to controls and the recovered joins are imprecise both Tcrbeta D-J and V-DJ rearrangements are detectable in thymic DNA but are variably reduced in level compared to controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: gammadelta T cell differentiation is promoted while alphabeta T cell differentiation is impaired compared to in wild-type mice T cell differentiation is partially arrested at DN3 unlike in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: T cells are 10% larger than controls both before and after stimulation T cells have increased mitochondrial mass relative to wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in cultures from bone marrow, DN4 cell proliferation is significantly reduced

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 2-3 fold reduction in expression of MHC class I on thymocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced expression of  MHC class I on all T cell classes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show the appearance of clonally-restricted, inactive yet functionally competent CD8 T cells, with an enrichment of CD8 T cells that lack glycosyl phosphatidylinositol (GPI) and GPI-anchored proteins in the blood, marrow, and spleen and enrichment of GPI<sup>-</sup> CD4 T cells in the spleen, and with pronounced Vbeta5.1/5.2 skewing of GPI<sup>-</sup> T cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mucosal-associated invariant T cells (MAIT) that express the canonical mVa19-Ja33 TCR rearrangement and are typically found in the gut lamina propia are virtually absent in these mice when wild-type bone marrow is transferred into these mice, MAIT T cells are found in the gut when these mice serve as bone marrow donors, MAIT T cells are absent in the gut of irradiated hosts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: CD8+/CD4+ T cell ratio is lower than wild-type or Irf2-deficient mice during course of LCMV infection

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: defective T-cell priming by antigen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: CD3 and CD28 antibody-activated T cells transfected with a retroviral cre-GPF exhibit impaired intra-lymph node migration compared with cells transfected with only GFP

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the frequency of naive T cells in contact with high-endothelial venules is increased compared to in wild-type mice T cells exhibit a 2-fold greater adhesion to ICAM-1 under flow compared with similarly treated wild-type cells migration of T cells on Transwell membranes is reduced compared with wild-type cells in adoptive transfer experiments, T cells exhibit shorter tracks, less displacement from their origin, reduced median speed, lower frequency of cells reaching peak instantaneous velocities, increased median turning angle, decreased average motility coefficient, and greater accumulation in lymph nodes due to impaired lymph node exit compared with wild-type cells naive T cells exhibit reduced Transwell chemotaxis in response to CCL21 compared with wild-type cells naive T cells exhibit inefficient crawling within a confined environment compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decreased survival of purified unstimulated T cells during in vitro neglect assays (cultured without stimulation)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 38% increase in the number of T cells that adhere to an ICAM-1 coated surface 41% and 27% reduction in chemotactic migration of T cells toward SDF-1alpha after 2 and 4 hours of adhesion, respectively reduction in the recruitment of T cells to wound sites

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: thymocytes lack Mg2+ inhibitable current

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: thymocytes show accelerated cell death in vitro

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: T cells hypersensitive to T cell receptor agonists

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mature T cells fail to flux calcium to any large extent in response to TCR cross-linking

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit fewer GPI<sup>-</sup> gamma-interferon producing CD8 T and CD4 T cells after lectin stimulation with myristate acetate and ionomycin

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell proliferation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: higher background proliferation rates hyperproliferation requires higher MOGp35-55 peptide concentrations as a stimulus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell subpopulation ratio
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: loss of CD8 T cells is more pronounced than loss of CD4 T cells, resulting in an elevated CD4:CD8 ratio

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T cell subpopulation ratio
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutants exhibit a slight increase in the CD4/CD8 T cell ratio

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T-helper 1 cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: exhibit impaired differentiation of precursor CD4+ T cells into effector T helper 1 cells but not T helper 2 cells even in the presence of IL-2, precursor CD4+ T cells fail to differentiate into Th1 cells that produce large amounts of the effector cytokine IFN-gamma IFN-gamma production is reduced in effector Th1 cells; impairment of IFN-gamma production in Th1 cells is caused by insufficient IL-12 stimulated differentiation of the precursor CD4+ T cells into effector Th1 cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T-helper 1 cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: dermal polarization towards pro-inflammatory T helper cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T-helper 1 cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: dermal polarization towards pro-inflammatory T helper cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T-helper 1 physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: under Th1 conditions, splenocytes produce less IFN-gamma than similarly treated wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T-helper 2 physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following immunization in vivo, splenocytes produce less TH2 cytokines (IL4, IL5, and IL13) compared with cells from similarly treated wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal T-helper 2 physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: under Th2 conditions, splenocytes produce less IL4, IL5, and IL13 compared with similarly treated wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Wallerian degeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: sciatic nerve shows active Wallerian degeneration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Z line morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cardiomyocytes show slightly thickened Z-discs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Z line morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: wider than in controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Z line morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Z lines are replaced by nemaline bodies appearing as distinct rod-like inclusions

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal Z line morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Z-lines are widened and disorganized in many myofibers

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal abducens nerve morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bilaterally affected mice have a 12% reduction in the number of distal abducens motor neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal abducens nerve morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the distal abducens nerves appear thin at E12.5 and are thinner at E15.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal accessory olfactory bulb morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: numbers of Grueneberg axonal bundles consisting of multiple axons do not avoid the accessory olfactory bulb as seen in control animals; axonal fibers and microglomeruli cross bulb from medial to lateral side some Grueneberg fibers end deep into the vomeronasal glomeruli primarily in rostral part  (not seen in controls)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal acrosome assembly
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cauda epididymal sperm exhibit abnormal acrosome formation: peanut-lectin (an acrosome marker) aggregates around the nucleus indicating abnormal acrosome localization TEM analysis revealed abnormally shaped acrosomes in developing spermatids

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal acrosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: spermatids from both adult and juvenile (22-26 days of age) male homozygotes display aberrant acrosome structures

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal acrosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: early round spermatids exhibit fragmentation of the acrosomal cap and abnormal large vesicles caused by defective fusion of the Golgi-derived transport vesicles to the acrosome elongated spermatids and epididymal spermatozoa display prominent acrosome vacuolization, loss of adhesion to the nucleus, and total acrosome loss

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal acrosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant acrosomes fail to acquire the crescent moon-shaped structure, are frequently fragmented, and abnormally positioned fragmentation of acrosomes occurs in the early stages of spermiogenesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal acrosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fragmented

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal actin cytoskeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: actin cytoskeleton disrupted in hippocampal cells, with abnormal clusters of cofilin and actin

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal actin cytoskeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P10, the actin cytoskeleton in chondrocytes is disorganized

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal actin cytoskeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in MEFs actin filaments are thin, disorganized and often fail to align with the direction of migration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal actin cytoskeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in MEFs actin filaments are thin, disorganized and often fail to align with the direction of migration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal actin cytoskeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in MEFs actin filaments are thin, disorganized and often fail to align with the direction of migration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal actin cytoskeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: embryos show an abnormal actin network with absence of proper actin fibers at the apical and basolateral boundary

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal action potential
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased 90 percent of depolarization (APD90) and Vmax of action potential in atrial cells at E15.5 fetal cardiomyocyte increased Vmax of action potential in ventricular cells at E15.5 fetal cardiomyocyte

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal action potential
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the response of nigral neurons to dopamine treatment exhibits a smaller amplitude and shorter duration of hyperpolarization than in similarly treated wild-type cells dopamine-treated nigral neurons exhibit a shorter time to predrug firing activity compared with similarly treated wild-type neurons quinpirole-treated nigral neurons are less sensitive than similarly treated wild-type neurons amphetamine-treated neurons exhibit a shorter cessation of firing compared with similarly treated wild-type neurons with smaller hyperpolarization

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal action potential
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: sciatic nerves have reduced amplitude of compound muscle action potential

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal action potential
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the abnormal action potential of cardiomycoytes at 80% repolarization is not prolonged to the extent wild-type cardiomyocytes are when LIF is administered

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal activated sperm motility
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: under capacitating conditions, activated cauda epididymal sperm exhibit a circulating swim path whereas wild-type sperm swim relatively straight

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal acute inflammation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: leukocyte infiltration is attenuated in the lungs after papain challenge

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adaptive immunity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following ovalbumin immunization, the memory response upon boosting with ovalbumin is 3-fold less than in similarly treated wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adenohypophysis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: inclusions are found in the anterior lobe of the pituitary

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adipose tissue development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit altered sorting of sortilin in adipocytes leading to inhibition of adipogenesis and lipodystrophy

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adipose tissue development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit altered sorting of sortilin in adipocytes leading to the inhibition of adipogenesis and lipodystrophy

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adipose tissue development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following adipogenic induction, mouse embryonic fibroblasts fail to re-enter cell cycle or differentiate into mature adipocytes unlike wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adipose tissue distribution
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the subcutaneous adipose tissue is thickened

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adipose tissue morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: desamethasone, 3-iso-butyl-1-methylxanthine and insulin (DMI)-induced adipocyte maturation of mouse embryonic fibroblasts is more effective than in similarly treated wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adrenal cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: disorganized cellular structure of adrenal cortex

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adrenal gland morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: inclusions are found in the adrenal gland

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adrenal gland physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cholesterol content decreased by 42%

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adrenal gland physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cholesterol content is 72% lower than normal

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adrenal gland secretion
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: adrenal chromaffin cells exhibit reduced catecholamine release per cell, quantal size, and frequency of release events when stimulated with high potassium ion compared to similarly treated wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adrenaline level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 81% reduction results in norepinephrine (synthesis reduced 50%) becoming the predominant adrenal catecholamine

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adrenergic chromaffin cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: marked reduction of secretory granules in chromaffin cells of adrenal increased number of apoptotic chromaffin cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adrenergic neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increase in the number of dermal adrenergic fibers

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adrenergic neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduction in the number of dermal adrenergic fibers

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal adrenocortical cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: adrenocortical cells have a reduction in mitochondria and smooth endoplasmic reticulum as well as an increased abundance of liposomes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aerobic respiration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: brown adipose tissue primary cells fail to exhibit increased oxygen consumption in response to isoproterenol treatment unlike wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aerobic respiration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced respiratory activity of mitochondria in muscle fibers

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aerobic respiration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impaired mitochondrial respiration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal afterhyperpolarization
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: both slow and medium after hyperpolarization (AHP) responses are decreased compared to in wild-type mice (slow AHP, -0.97+/-0.13 mV compared to -0.3+/-0.05 mV in wild-type mice; medium AHP, -1.8+/-0.15 mV to -1.35+/-0.1 mV in wild-type mice)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal airway resistance
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following methacholine treatment, ovalbumin sensitized and challenged mice fail to exhibit an increase in airway resistance unlike similarly treated wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal alisphenoid bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the mediocaudal region of the alisphenoid bone is missing

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal allantois morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bulbous at E9.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal alveolar lamellar body morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: smaller at E17.5 but still able to synthesize surfactant protein C

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal alveolar process morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hypoplasia of the periodontal alveolar bone and enamel

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ameloblast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: loss of polarization

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ameloblast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: accelerated ameloblast differentiation in incisors

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ameloblast morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the ameloblast layer arrangement in the molar tooth germs at E18.5 exhibits an irregular shape

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: under fasting conditions, have lower amino acid levels in the heart, liver and brain 10 hours after, but not immediately after, caesarean delivery

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fasting results in no reduction in intramuscular concentrations of leucine and glutamine as compared to fasted wild-type mice intramuscular leucine concentration is not increased after leucine injection intramuscular leucine and isoleucine concentrations are increased in relation to increase in dietary protein; in wild-type mice concentrations remain the same plasma leucine concentration is unchanged in response to increases in dietary protein on a 30%  protein diet, leucine, isoleucine and glutamine accumulate at higher levels in muscle relative to wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after birth (P2-P14) and in adult stages (>P40), brain levels of branched-chain amino acids (BCAAs), esp. leucine and isoleucine, are abnormally low while levels of a few other amino acids (e.g., histidine, serine, and phenylalanine) are increased relative to those in age-matched controls brain histidine levels are several fold higher than in control mice brain levels of leucine and isoleucine are normalized after 3 weeks of intracerebroventricular (i.c.v.) BCAA (leucine and isoleucine) delivery

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decreased amino acid levels in the embryo

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: skeletal tissues have elevated levels of alanine, arginine, asparagine, histidine, isoleucine, methionine, phenylalanine, proline, threonine, tryptophan, and valine liver tissues have elevated levels of asparagine, isoleucine, lysine proline, serine, threonine, and valine

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased levels of asymmetric dimethyl arginine in lung, liver, and kidney symmetric dimethyl arginine is elevated by about 60% only in lung

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tissue levels of ADMA and L-NMMA are significantly increased in homozygous mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following overnight culture in Krebs buffer, mutant aortas show a 50% increase in asymmetrical dimethylarginine (ADMA) release

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: citrulline levels are increased by 14% in the basal ganglia region pipecoic acid levels, a catabolite of lysine, are higher in all parts of the brain, with increases ranging from 23% in the midbrain to 33% in the cortex

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: total free amino acid content is reduced in the stratum corneum and the distribution of amino acids in the stratum corneum is altered, with decreased levels of arginine, glycine, histidine, and serine

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: total free amino acid content is reduced in the stratum corneum and the distribution of amino acids in the stratum corneum is altered, with decreased levels of arginine, glycine, histidine, and serine

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid metabolism
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced purine biosynthesis, most severely in cerebellum and cerebral cortex

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amino acid metabolism
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show abnormal activation of the amino acid response (AAR) signal transduction pathway in the brain

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amniotic fluid composition
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E17.5, alkaline phosphatase activity is significantly reduced

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal amygdala morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: neuronal vacuolation is present to some extent

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal angiogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: limited new blood vessel formation in the liver angiogenesis observed the cardiac muscle of 8 of 10 mice examined

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal angiogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hypervasculatization of the bone

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal angiogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: postnatal tamoxifen treatment from P1-P3 to delete Jag1 in endothelial cells results in significant decreases in numbers of filopodia and filopodia-extending endothelial tip cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal angiogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: blood vessel proliferation in dermis is observed, with tortuous dilated capillaries present in superficial dermis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal angiogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: persistent directional migration of primary mouse cardiac endothelial cells (MCECs) is reduced and capillary density is reduced in E14.5-E16.5 hearts, indicating abnormal microvascular angiogenesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal angiogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show defective retinal angiogenesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal angiogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: angiogenic response after carotid ligation is more moderate than in controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anterior cardinal vein morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E9.0 irregularly formed large vessels (anterior cardinal veins and dorsal aorta) with defective lumens are seen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anterior commissure morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit a thinning and/or absent midline crossing of the anterior commissure throughout its anterior-posterior axis compared with wild-type mice the anterior-posterior axis appears tortuous and often has aberrant fiber projections at the midline unlike in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anterior commissure morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the anterior commissure is thinner at the midline compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anterior commissure morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: anterior commissure disrupted

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anterior commissure pars posterior morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the majority of fibers in the posterior branch of the anterior commissure fail to cross the midline

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anterior definitive endoderm morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: E7.5 embryos exhibit a modest displacement of the anterior definitive endoderm towards the distal tip compared to wild-type embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anterior uvea morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: melanophagy in the iris or the ciliary body

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anterior visceral endoderm cell migration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 6 of 11 mice exhibit anterior visceral endoderm (AVE) migration defects compared with wild-type mice 9 of 12 mice exhibit abnormal swirling of AVE cells compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anterior visceral endoderm cell migration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 6 of 14 mice exhibit anterior visceral endoderm migration defects compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anterior visceral endoderm morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: E6.5 embryos exhibit aberrant distal visceral endoderm/anterior visceral endoderm localization, with a displacement at the distal tip

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal anxiety-related response
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased transition between light and dark areas in a light-dark box assay

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta elastic fiber morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: progressive fragmentation of elastic fibers within the medial wall beginning around 2 months of age elastic fiber calcification is occasionally seen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta elastic fiber morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fibers have an abnormal wavy, thin appearance and are fragmented and discontinuous within the aneurysm

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta elastic tissue morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: elastic lamellae in the aorta are about 50% thinner 5% and 25% increase in elastic lamellae in the descending and ascending aorta, respectively

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta elastic tissue morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormalities in the lamellar unit are seen both inside and outside of the aortic aneurysm the elastic lamellae appear thin and disorganized beginning between P10 and P14

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal positioning of the aorta and pulmonary trunk

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the aortic trunk is thinner than normal

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following nephrectomy (to induce chronic kidney disease) and administration of tamoxifen, mice developed smaller calcified medial lesions than nephrectomized controls and similar to sham-operated controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 6 of 9 show thinning of the wall of the proximal ascending aorta, suggesting aneurismal dilation exhibit focal fragmentation of elastic fibers, accumulation of amorphous matrix and dissection of blood into the aortic media (aortic dissection) chronic lesions in the aorta show expansion of the intramural thrombus, recruitment of inflammatory cells and an adventitial reaction of cellular proliferation when the full thinckness of the wall is breached

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice from mothers on the acceleration diet during pregnancy and also fed this diet exhibit extensive mineralization in the aorta

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta tunica adventitia morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 12 of 20 exhibit adventitia hyperplasia with inflammation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta tunica intima morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 6 of 20 exhibit intimal hyperplasia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta tunica media morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the endoluminal layer is surrounded by a poorly organized and dissociated tunica media

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta tunica media morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 9 of 20 exhibit medial necrosis and vasculitis 8 of 20 exhibit medial calcification

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta tunica media morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: aortic media is thickened compared to in wild-type mice at 3 months, enlarged media in mice on a 129/Sv congenic  background is stronger than in mice on a C57BL/6 congenic background mice on a congenic 129/Sv background exhibit wide clinical variability

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta tunica media morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 9 months, aortic media is thickened compared to in wild-type mice however, mice on a C57BL/6 congenic background are asymptomatic at 3 months unlike mice on a 129/Sv congenic background

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta wall morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: inner and outer diameters of the aorta become progressively smaller, starting at E17.5 by P2.5, show a 76% increase in the number of cells in the aorta resulting in subendothelial accumulation of cells that eventually obliterates the vascular lumen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aorta wall morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: progressive deterioration within the medial layer, with elastic fiber fragmentation and disarray of vascular smooth muscle cells begins around 2 months of age however, no intimal hyperplasia, aortic inflammation, or aortic dissection are detected and life span is similar to wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aortic arch and aortic arch branch attachment
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E12.5 the left subclavian artery arises from the right sided arch of the aorta

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aortic arch morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: all newborns have abnormalities in the arch of the aorta

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aortic arch morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hypoplastic transverse arch, transverse arch obstruction, interrupted aortic arch and vascular sling

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aortic arch morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: various defects

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aortic valve annulus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: aortic valves exhibit extracellular matrix structural abnormalities including proteoglycan accumulation in the annulus region and abnormal cartilage-like nodule formation in subareas of the annulus, specifically near the commissures and aortic-mitral continuity nodules are characterized by chondrocyte-like halo-cell morphology and are seen at all stages, indicating a developmental abnormality preceding the development of aortic valve disease proteoglycan accumulation is seen only in aged mutants MMP expression in the annulus indicates early maladaptive extracellular matrix (ECM) remodeling in aortic valve malformation without aortic valve disease and worsening pathologic ECM remodeling with aortic valve disease

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aortic valve cusp morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 10% of mice exhibit aortic valve leaflets that are thickened and/or fused with clear evidence of chondrification

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aortic valve cusp morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 25% of neonates exhibit aortic valve tricuspids with thick leaflets 25% of neonates exhibit aortic valve bicuspids with thick leaflets 20% of neonates have an aortic valve bicuspid or unicuspid with an overgrown and obstructed leaflet in 2 surviving mice the aortic valve leaflets are thickened and in one fused with clear evidence of chondrification

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aortic valve cusp morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 25% of neonates exhibit aortic valve tricuspids with thick leaflets 4.2% of neonates exhibit aortic valve bicuspids with thick leaflets 8.3% of neonates have an aortic valve bicuspid or unicuspid with an overgrown and obstructed leaflet

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aortic valve cusp morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P5, the mutant aortic valves have 3 leaflets, as expected; however, these leaflets appear relatively dysplastic

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal aortic valve morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: aged mutants exhibit extracellular matrix abnormalities such as an increase in cleaved versican in the cusp and annulus regions, increase in total proteoglycan content and decrease in type I and III collagens in the aortic valves

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal apical ectodermal ridge morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the apical ectodermal ridge morphology is disrupted

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal apolipoprotein level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: secretion of apoB-100 as VLDL1 is increased 2 fold from hepatocytes isolated from mice on high fat diet (HFD) as compared to control on HFD 40% increase in 35S labeled apoB-100 is found in VLDL1 plasma fractions from mice on high fat diet (HFD) as compared to control HFD-fed mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal apoptosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cell death is increased in knock-out cells in vitro after applying different apoptotic stimuli

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal apoptosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: TUNEL analysis revealed the presence of numerous apoptotic vascular cells in homozygous null embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal appendicular skeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: smaller appendicular elements

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal appendicular skeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: smaller appendicular elements,  intermediate to homozygous mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal appendicular skeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygotes exhibit endochondral defects throughout the appendicular skeleton

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal arrector pilli muscle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at necropsy (16 weeks of age), mice fed a high-fat diet exhibit normal skin but unusually prominent arrector pili muscles

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal arterial thrombosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: exhibit thrombosis of the aortic wall

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal arteriole morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice lack defined coronary arterioles

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal artery development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal development of several different arteries (pulmonary arteriole, internal mammary artery, subclavian artery, and abdominal aorta)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal artery morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygous null embryos displayed loss of vascular integrity in large arteries (e.g. the dorsal aorta and umbilical arteries)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal artery morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increase in arterial stiffness

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal artery morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increase in cellularity and reduction in luminal diameter in systemic and pulmonary arteries of all sizes, including distributing arteries and arterioles

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal artery morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: thin arterial walls are seen in the thoracic, abdominal, and carotid arteries

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal articular cartilage morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: articular cartilage is distorted with chondrocytes and stromal cells in the synovium and meniscus, and shows cytoplasmic distention caused by lysosomal storage

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal articular cartilage morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: articular cartilage is somewhat distorted with chondrocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal articular cartilage morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: articular cartilage is somewhat distorted with chondrocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal astrocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: protoplasmic astrocytes in cerebellum have enlarged vacuoles in cytoplasm, surrounding Purkinje cells there are numerous slightly electron dense granules, often containing membrane remnants, filling cytoplasm of protoplasmic astrocytes, endothelial cells and pericytes surrounding capillaries

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal astrocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: longer processes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal astrocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: glial fibrillary acidic protein(GFAP)-positive astrocytes are not present in the marginal zone of cervical spinal cord of E18.5 embryos GFAP-positive acstrocytes do no develop from neural explants of E14.5 cerebral cortices in the presence of IL-6, ciliary neurotrophic factor, or oncostatin M

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal astrocyte physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: astrocytes taken from 6 to 8 week old homozygotes and cultured for 14 to 16 days have diminished ATP-stimulated calcium signaling with capacitative calcium entry in these astrocytes found to be only 45% that of controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal astrocyte physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: astrocytes taken from 6 to 8 week old homozygotes and cultured for 14 to 16 days have diminished ATP-stimulated calcium signalling with capacitative calcium entry in these astrocytes reduced by 43% compared with controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal atrial thrombosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in severely affected mice at 1 year

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal atrial thrombosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: one quarter of adults have atrial thrombosis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal atrial thrombosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hearts show thrombi in enlarged atria at around 6 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal atrioventricular cushion morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: atrioventricular cushion defects arise at E17.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal atrioventricular cushion morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E15.5 when outflow tract endocardial cushions in wild-type mice have begun to thin into leaflets, the pulmonary and aortic cushions remain thick indicating defects in valve remodeling

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal atrioventricular cushion morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: defective development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal atrioventricular cushion morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hypocellular atrioventricular cushion at E9.25 is caused by reduced mesenchyme formation, with the number of mesenchymal cells in atrioventricular cushions reduced to about 30% of the control level at the initial stage of cushion mesenchymal cell formation (about E9.5) the number of mesenchymal cells formed from atrioventricular cushion explants is reduced expression of Sema6C is increased in atrioventricular cushions, in both endocardial and mesenchymal cells, starting from E9.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal atrioventricular septum morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: atrial septum closure defect (ASD) is associated with an underdeveloped atrioventricular septum

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal atrium myocardial trabeculae morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: atrial trabecular formation is impaired such that trabeculae at E14.5 are short and stubby

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal auditory brainstem response
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 10-week old mice show significant functional loss in peripheral auditory sensitivity relative to wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal auditory brainstem response waveform shape
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: amplitude of the first wave is significantly diminished in response to a range of frequencies and sound intensities

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal auditory brainstem response waveform shape
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: significant reduction in ABR wave I amplitudes at 24 kHz in older homozygous mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal auditory brainstem response waveform shape
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ABR wave I amplitudes from 5.6 kHz and upwards are reduced at high stimulus intensities (suprathreshold)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal auditory tube morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: eustachian tube's medial osseus segment and opening within the tympanic cavity (OpTC) are abnormal and diminuitive, being about half the size of wild-type opening within the tympanic cavity (OpTC) is narrowed and abnormally positioned at the anterior perimeter of the middle ear some mice have a polyp obstructing the OpTC

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal auditory tube morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: amorphous tissue is found in the Eustachian tubes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal autophagosome formation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts (MEFs) fail to form autophagosomes when deprived of nutrients

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal autophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in retina pigmented epithelium (RPE) cells of mutants, degenerating phagosomes with undigested photoreceptor outer segment (POS) material are observed in contrast to controls where POS are in single-membrane phagosomes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal autophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: complete loss of autophagy in hypothalamus neurons whether mice are fed a normal or high-fat diet

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal autophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 20 months, kidneys exhibit impaired autophagy-lysosomal pathways compared with wild-type kidneys

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal autophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: expression analysis indicates increased autophagy in MEFs and in the liver

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal autophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced expression of autophagy regulators in intestinal epithelia, the mesenchymal compartment, and in cecal patches after infection with Salmonella typhimurium

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal autophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: IECs (intestinal epithelial cells) display loss of homeostatic autophagy

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal autophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: dramatically reduced in neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal autophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant MEFs show increased levels of lipidated LC3 relative to wild-type MEFs, indicating impaired autolysosomal clearance; however, autophagy is not entirely blocked as LC3-II levels are further increased upon treatment with bafilomycin A1 upon sustained (14 h) serum starvation, mutant MEFs show impaired recovery of lysosomes, consistent with a defect in autophagic lysosome reformation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal autophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: electron microscopy of NMJs on the EHL muscle revealed swollen presynaptic terminals with membranous aggregates abnormal vesicular structures are found near the EHL muscle fiber surface; some aggregates are surrounded by a double membrane typical of autophagosomes in skeletal muscle (tibialis anterior), occasional myofibers show abnormal accumulations of autophagosomes and/or lysosomes in their center

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axial skeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: smaller axial elements

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axial skeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: smaller axial elements, intermediate to homozygous mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axial skeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: severe defects including a shortened axial skeleton at E17.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axial skeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygotes display axial defects along the entire vertebral column

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axial skeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: dysplasia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axial skeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 8 weeks of age, rigidity of the vertebral column

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axial skeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: changes are more pronounced and occur earlier in the superior spine than in the inferior spine

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon extension
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: neurons in the cerebral cortex and hippocampal CA1 region extend about 4-fold more collateral branches from the primary axon and these branches are longer low density cultures of hippocampal neurons display longer collateral branches which form longer tertiary and quaternary branches and active shrinkage of these collaterals is reduced compared to wild-type neurons microtubule depolymerization is reduced in the growth cones of cultured mutant hippocampal neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon extension
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: oculomotor nerve neurons show failure of axon elongation to the orbit; this nerve growth failure precedes motor neuron apoptosis developing axons of the oculomotor nerves superior division stall in the proximal nerve, and the growth cones enlarge, extend excessive filopodia, and assume random trajectories while inferior division axons reach the orbit but branch ectopically

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon extension
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit increased neurite length and branching compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon extension
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in primary cultures, Schwann cells isolated from dorsal root and nerves exhibit 2 times longer cell processes compared with wild-type cells longer processes in cultured motor neurons from E14.5 spinal cords 3 times longer neurites from cultured P7 cerebella neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon extension
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: E18.5 brains show severe impairment of axonal elongation of cortical commissural axons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon extension
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice electroporated with a cre recombinase vector in the brain exhibit impaired axonal elongation of cortical commissural axons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon extension
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: accelerated axonal outgrowth in cultured neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon guidance
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: guidance of ophthalmic nerve axons and cutaneous sensory neurons was abnormal so that projections extended beyond their normal zones

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon guidance
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: growth cone collapse of dorsal root ganglion and sympathetic ganglion axons in response to Sema3A was completely abolished

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon guidance
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E11.5 to E12, guidance and branching of cranial nerves is defective compared to in wild-type mice mice exhibit defective guidance of commissural axons and cranial nerves compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon initial segment morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hypertrophic or exhibiting abnormal blebs at 2 months

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon initial segment morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hypertrophic or exhibiting abnormal blebs at 2 months transgene expression of the LC2 isoform doesnt not rescue the axon initial segment phenotype

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: irregularities are detected at the axon-myelin interface including; irregular width of the extracellular periaxonal space and occasional apparent fusion of the adaxonal glial membrane with the axonal membrane occasionally the axon-myelin apposition is severely disturbed rarely invaginations of the oligodendroglial plasma membrane into the axoplasm are seen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: irregularities are detected at the axon-myelin interface including; irregular width of the extracellular periaxonal space and occasional apparent fusion of the adaxonal glial membrane with the axonal membrane occasionally the axon?myelin apposition is severely disturbed rarely invaginations of the oligodendroglial plasma membrane into the axoplasm are seen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the facial nerve axon bundle is extensively defasciculated during migration unlike in wild-type mice many horizontally running neurites, identified as axonal collateral branches, are seen in the brain

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: oculomotor explant axons have normal growth but enlarged growth cones and increased filopodia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: axon length and branch number are increased in cultured cortical neurons callosal axons grow further into the contralateral hemisphere at P4 at P14, axon distribution in the corpus callosum is disturbed with a greater number of axon terminals, with a wider distribution in both the S1 and S2 regions broader distribution of the contralateral axon projection pattern in the corpus callosum

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: significant reduction in axonal diameter on the sciatic nerve at P9 relative to wild-type controls shift in the frequency distribution towards a thinner axon diameter and an increased g-ratio in lumbar L4 and L5 dorsal roots at P9

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: axonal swelling in the cerebral cortex, nucleus gracilis, posterior thalamic nucleus, hippocampus, inferior colliculus, tricaudal pons and reticular nucleus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the number of small myelinated axons in the phrenic nerves is increased compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: axonal torpedos beginning at 6 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutants exhibit progressive increase in periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive granules, first seen in the proximal axons and perinuclear space of large neurons and later in distal parts of axons granules are mitochondria with degenerative inner membranes collapse of mitochondria in axons is accompanied by focal disappearance of the cytoskeleton

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the average size of unmyelinated axons in the sciatic nerve is smaller than in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the average size of unmyelinated axons in the sciatic nerve is smaller than in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: longer than in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygotes exhibit axonal swelling in the sciatic nerve

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: axon swelling in sciatic nerves

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: axon swelling in sciatic nerves

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the number of axons affected appear to increase with age of the mouse swollen axons seen in mutant mice are a unique axonal dystrophy

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: axonal swellings resulting from accumulations of organelles and neurofilaments are observed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: significantly increased number of dystrophic swellings observed in foot pad intraepidermal sensory nerve fibers relative to wild-type controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 10-12 months, homozygotes display a 30% reduction in axonal diameter, as shown in axons of the optic nerve

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon pruning
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: sympathetic neurons of the superior cervical ganglion (SCG) have improper pruning of axons from neurons that reach into both eye compartments by 50 days of age, wild-type mice prune axons from SCG so that only 36% of SCG neurons reach into both eyes mutant mice have less axon pruning, which leads to 51% of SCG neurons projecting into both eyes at 50 days of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon radial sorting
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P6, mutant sciatic nerves have thinner myelin sheaths with several dysmyelinated areas where unmyelinated axons of all calibers are grouped in bundles, in an unsorted manner
