OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axon radial sorting
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit defective radial sorting of nerve roots in the spinal cord

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axonal transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in axons from mutant mice, retrograde axonal transport is impaired

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axonal transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impairment of retrograde axonal transport in symptomatic mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal axonal transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: transport of dopamine-beta-hydrolase in nerves is reduced compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal baroreceptor physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal barrel cortex morphology

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: small basal ganglia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal basal lamina morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal basal lamina morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal base-excision repair

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal basement membrane morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal basement membrane morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal basement membrane morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal basisphenoid bone morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice display behavioral defects despite normal grip strength and coordination of movement at 8 weeks post-infection with scrapie strain Rocky Mountain Laboratories, mice display reduced burrowing (displacing 54+/-7% of pellets compared to 73+/-4% at week 7) that continues to deteriorate into week 9(45+/-6%) but recovers by week 10

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal behavior

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal behavioral response to amphetamine

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal behavioral response to anesthetic

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal bile secretion

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal blood circulation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following reperfusion of an ischemic heart ex vivo, rate pressure product is increased (16+/-1.3 compared to 10+/-2.1 beats per minute mm Hg x10<sup>-3</sup> in wild-type mice), cardiac work is increased (5.7+/-0.6 compared to 2.3+/-0.8 ml per minute mm Hg x10<sup>-2</sup> in wild-type mice), aortic flow is increased (5.5+/-0.9 compared to 1.5+/-0.6 ml per minute in wild-type mice), and cardiac power is increased (61.4+/-6.9 compared to 25.2+/-9.1 mJ per minute in wild-type mice) recovery after cardiac ischemia is improved 2.5-fold compared to in wild-type mice and mice recover almost 80% of their preischemic values

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal blood coagulation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal blood coagulation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal blood homeostasis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal blood homeostasis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal blood homeostasis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal blood homeostasis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle checkpoint function

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle checkpoint function
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in colcemid and taxol treated mouse embryonic fibroblasts not worsened by treatment with ZM447439 (aurora B kinase inhibitor)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle checkpoint function
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: embryo sections show increased numbers of bright pH3 foci (pH3, a marker of dividing cells) relative to controls, suggesting that cells arrest in the G2/late G2 phase analysis of the phosphorylation status of Cdc25c (cell division cycle 25C) at serine 216 (S216) shows that embryos exhibit significantly more phospho-Cdc25c foci than littermates and stage-matched controls, indicating cell cycle arrest at the G2/M checkpoint

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle checkpoint function
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after nocodazole treatment the time for 50% of cells to exit prometaphase arrest is reduced to 1.1 hours compared to 7.2 hours for wild-type MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle checkpoint function
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after nocodazole treatment the time for 50% of cells to exit prometaphase arrest is reduced to 3.8 hours compared to 7.2 hours for wild-type MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle checkpoint function
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after nocodazole treatment the time for 50% of cells to exit prometaphase arrest is reduced to 5.3 hours compared to 7.2 hours for wild-type MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle checkpoint function
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cultured MEFs show a significant accumulation of cells in G2/M compared to wild-type cells (41% vs 27%), with concurrent decreases in cells in G1 and S phases

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle checkpoint function
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tamoxifen-treated embryonic stem cells exhibit a defect in cell growth at G2/M phase unlike wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle checkpoint function
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cell cycle progression of the dentate migration stream is impaired at E15.5, most likely through the G1 phase; defects at E15.5 are smaller than those at or after P10

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cycle checkpoint function
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cell cycle analysis on E12.5 fetal gonads showed a significantly higher % of mutant germ (MVH+) cells in G2/M and a corresponding reduction in the % of germ cells in G1 relative to wild-type controls phosphorylated histone H3 and TUNEL labeling, both indicative of G2/M checkpoint activation, are significantly increased in mutant germ cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell cytoskeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: collapse of mitochondria in axons is accompanied by focal disappearance of the cytoskeleton

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell death
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased cell death in mouse embryonic fibroblasts within 5 to 6 days of treatment with a cre-expressing lentivirus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell death
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased sensitivity to heat stress was seen in bone marrow cells and fibroblasts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell death
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: without prior conditioning, mouse embryonic cells exhibit decreased viability when heat-shocked for 15 or 45 minutes increased viability following heat-shock was reduced when mouse embryonic cells were preconditioned

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 100% of mouse embryonic fibroblasts (MEFs) can be induced to differentiate into adipose cells compared to 5% of wild-type cells some MEFs undergone spontaneous differentiation into adipose cells unlike wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts exhibit increased ability to differentiate into mature adipocytes compared with similarly treated wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: adipose derived stem cells (ADSCs) infected with a cre expressing adenovirus and exposed to an adipogenic hormone cocktail accumulate fewer lipids and show attenuated expression of adipocyte markers and enhanced expression of smooth muscle cell markers differentiation of ADSCs, infected with a cre expressing adenovirus and treated with TGFB, into smooth muscle cells is enhanced

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell migration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a transwell assay indicates that directional cell migration is impaired in MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell migration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in a wound healing assay MEFs close the wound more rapidly compared to wild-type controls a transwell assay indicates that directional cell migration is impaired in MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell migration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in a wound healing assay MEFs close the wound more rapidly compared to wild-type controls a transwell assay indicates that directional cell migration is impaired in MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: primary dermal fibroblasts have an increase in the number of actin stress fibers and vinculin-positive focal adhesion contacts, however see no alterations in tubulin and vimentin network

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fibroblasts exhibit a higher level of dynactin and restin at microtubule tips, however observe no differences in microtubule dynamics

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: on average microtubule density is decreased by about 51% both in and outside of the nervous system at 20 to 26 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: higher number of late endosomal and lysosomal vesicles in mouse embryonic fibroblasts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5, cells of the cerebellum exhibit abnormal mitochondrial and autophagic-like vacuoles compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts (MEFs) display a compact, round morphology instead of the normal fibroblast-like irregular shape and are smaller MEFs exhibit strongly bundled F-actin and increased amount of peripheral F-actin MEFs show an increase in the number of Rab6 vesicles at the cell periphery in areas of dense F-actin bundles, however overall density of Rab6 vesicles is unchanged

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: MEFs treated with arsenite produce fewer and smaller stress granules than do controls stress granules disappear more rapidly than in controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: elevation of hexuronic acid levels in tissues indicating glycosaminoglycan storage

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell nucleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: nuclei of neural plate cells are rounder with width: length ratio of 1.44 compared to the elongated and ellipsoid wild-type nuclei that have average width:length ratio of 2.33

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell nucleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the numbers of chromocenters per nucleus in the ventricular zone are greatly decreased; this is due to hyperclustering of chromocenters and not due to loss of chromocenters hyperclustering of chromocenters occurs in neural stem cells and in postmitotic neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell nucleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: micronuclei due to lagging chromosomes in mouse embryonic fibroblasts, regenerating hepatocytes and hepatocellular carcinoma

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell nucleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: micronuclei in mouse embryonic fibroblasts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell nucleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased numbers of micronuclei in mouse embryonic fibroblasts indicating genomic instability

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: liver DNA from double mutants exhibits more than a 2-fold elevation in spontaneous mutations (single base substitutions) compared to Ogg1-sufficient gpt hemizygotes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutation frequency is higher than in Ogg1-wild-type transgenic animals; frequency tends to increase after liver regeneration following partial hepatectomy spectrum of mutations in cultured mutant liver cells shows an increase in number transverions (GC->AT) and number of deletion mutations is increased during liver regeneration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tamoxifen-treated mouse embryonic fibroblasts exhibit decreased cis-PTase activity in isolated membranes and mannose incorporation into proteins compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts exhibit compromised in vivo pluripotency compared to wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant MEFs display impaired retinoic acid receptor activity; in contrast, cAMP-dependent signaling appears unaffected

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: autophagosomes formation in the brain is impaired

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in vitro, MEFs derived from homozygous mutant mice display severely reduced TAK1 kinase activities and decreased sensitivity to TGF-beta stimulation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tamoxifen-treated embryonic stem cells exhibit global chromosomal decondensation at interphase compared to in wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 4-hydroxytamoxifen (4-HT) treated MEFs are hypersensitive to hydroxyurea and aphidicolin, showing decreased colony forming after exposure

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in vitro, isolated primary kidney cells show consistently reduced binding to artificial calcium phosphate particles (aCPP) relative to wild-type kidney cells binding between aCPP to mutant kidney cells without heparin is comparable to binding between aCPP to wild-type cells in the presence of heparin, indicating that Fbln7 deletion is as effective as heparin administration on aCPP binding

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increase in the extra-cellular acidification rate and lactate production in MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice tissues exhibit accumulated oligosaccharides compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced histone H3K23 acetylation in E10.5 embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced histone H3K23 acetylation in cortex extracts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced histone H3K23 acetylation in extracts and mouse embryonic fibroblasts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced histone H3K23 acetylation in thymus and spleen extracts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: expression of ATF6-dependent unfolded protein response genes is reduced in homozygous mutants upon activation of the endoplasmic reticulum stress

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ES cells do not grow significantly in control media

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygotes exhibit a severely impaired cell volume regulation, as assessed in proximal renal tubules and hippocampal neurons, and a moderately raised intraneuronal Cl<sup>-</sup> concentration relative to wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a significant reduction of beta1-adrenergic receptor levels is observed in hippocampal lysates, suggesting that Gopc stabilizes its interacting G-protein-coupled receptors

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts fail to recruit IFT proteins to the basal body and retain the cilium-suppressing centrosomal protein CP110 at the distal mother centriole

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: primary MEFs derived from mutant E12.5-E13.5 embryos show reduced viability by trypan blue exclusion relative to wild-type MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts exhibit increased DNA damage when cultured in high oxygen compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts exposed to RAS-induced transformation exhibit 4- to 10-fold fewer colonies than similarly treated wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts exhibit leakiness of residual end joining in a transient V(D)J recombination end joining assay compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cells from null mice show a reduced ability to rejoin DNA double-strand breaks than wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in Rag1 and Rag2 transfected mutant MEFs, recovery of plasmids harboring recombination signal sequence (RS) joins is reduced by 10 to 20-fold, while that of plasmids harboring coding joins is reduced by 200-fold

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts (MEFs) exhibit minor changes in endoplasmic reticulum calcium ion capacity compared with wild-type cells MEFs exhibit a small increase in the unfolded protein response (UPR) compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: thapsigargin-treated mouse embryonic fibroblasts exhibit enhanced store-operated calcium entry compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ES cells adhere less to feeder cells compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ES cells adhere less to feeder cells compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ES cells adhere less to feeder cells compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cells accumulate inosine nucleotides unlike wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: quisqualate (QA) treatment of Purkinje neurons elicited a similar calcium release as controls; repeated QA application showed a less attenuated response in mutant cells than in controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in vitro, MEFs derived from homozygous mutant mice exhibit a 70% and 60% reduction in tyrosine kinase activity of c-Src and Fyn, respectively, as determined by measuring the amount of <sup>32</sup>P incorporated into an exogenous substrate (enolase), along with a concomitant increase in c-Src Tyr527 phosphorylation reduced c-Src kinase activity is also noted in tissue lysates from homozygous mutant mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular cholesterol metabolism
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tamoxifen-treated mouse embryonic fibroblasts accumulate free cholesterol compared with control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular cholesterol metabolism
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: eggs harvested at ~16 h after hCG administration show abnormally high levels of unesterified cholesterol relative to control eggs, as assessed by filipin staining

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular glucose uptake
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: glucose uptake is increased by 50% in MEFs compared to wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular replicative senescence
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: senescence associated markers are increased in kidneys from 5 month old mutants compared to wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular replicative senescence
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the number of senescent cells is increased compared to wild-type MEFs or MEFs double heterozygous for Rae1<sup>tm1Jvd</sup> and Bub3<sup>tm1Jvd</sup>

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular replicative senescence
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fewer senescence cells surrounding the hepatic central veins in CCl4-treated mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular respiration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impaired mitochondrial respiration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular respiration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: enhanced glycolysis and an decrease in ATP content in MEFs increase in O2 consumption rates and fatty acid oxidation in MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular respiration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show alteration in mRNA expression of genes typical for slow twitch type I fibers, urea cycle, and glycolytic pathway in the gastrocnemius but not the soleus muscle and a decrease of mitochondrial enzyme SDH and Cox staining suggesting reduced mitochondrial oxidative activity

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular respiration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts cultured from E9.5 homozygous mutant embryos (which do not yet respire aerobically) are not viable, indicating a role in cellular respiration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cellular respiration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tamoxifen-treated mice exhibit compromised mitochondrial respiration due to defects in protein lipoylation and respiratory complexes compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal centrosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decrease in the number of centrosomes in embryonic neural epithelium

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ceramide level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduction in C16-C1P ceramides in the retina but increased ceramide levels compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar Purkinje cell layer
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: some Purkinje cells are found in the white matter at P12 rings of proliferating granule cells are found at the periphery of Purkinje cells islands

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in cortex, macrophages completely encircling neurons are observed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fragmented into multiple groups or islands of Purkinjie cells at P0, PLAP-expressing cells (parallel fibers) are intermingled with CaBP-positive Purkinje cells within the cerebellar plate, rather than confined to the upper external granule layer

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar foliation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abberant patterns at 15 days of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar foliation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P10 to P45, the intraculminate, declival and uvular fissures are poorly developed or missing in the mutant cerebellum and lobe IV/V is elongated and folia VI/VII appear to be particularly affected; at P20, reduced depth of the intracrural fissure is also seen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar foliation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P0

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar foliation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P5 and P7 hypoplasia of cerebellar folia is seen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar foliation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: absence of precentral and intercrural fissures, other fissures are less pronounced, lobules I-III and VI-VII are fused and most folia are irregular a midline cleft in lobule X is present

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar foliation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E17.5, only a partially formed cerebellar primordium with an incomplete external granule cell layer (EGL) is present regardless of whether or not embryos developed exencephaly

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar foliation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: development of cerebellar folia is defective, with mutants exhibiting fusion between adjacent folia with age, folia become progressively more distorted with decreased depth of the folia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar granule cell migration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P20, granule cell precursors (GCP) are present in the external granule layer, which were absent in age-matched controls, indicating a delay in GCP migration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar granule cell migration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: migration of granule cell precursors from explants cultured on laminin or laminin and Sema4c is impaired compared to in wild-type explants

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar granule cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: apoptosis is detected in granular cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar granule cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the number of granule cell progenitors (GCPs) in the stream migrating towards the developing dentate gyrus is reduced and migration towards the Ammon's horn is entirely disbanded retardation of GCP migration is visible at E17.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar granule cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the endoplasmic reticulum of granule neurons is swollen and fragmented in mice prior to the onset of disease the transgenic Prnp protein localizes in the ER of these cells instead of in the plasma membrane like the endogenous protein

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar granule layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: perturbation in the granule layer occur mainly in the rostral and caudal folia the granule layer is almost completely absent from the base of some folia and its architecture is disorganized with cells from upper and lower layers intermingling the base of some folia lack the cerebellar granule layer

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar lobule formation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: anterobasal cardinal lobe, appears abnormal at P0 and P2

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar lobule formation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: adult mice display underdevelopment of the rostral lobules with fusion of lobules 1-3, similar to Plxnb2tm1Matl homozygotes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar molecular layer
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: by 2 years of age, morphological alterations of Purkinje cells and Bergmann glia are observed in the molecular layer of the cerebellum

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar molecular layer
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: numerous proteinase K-resistant prion protein aggregates are present

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellar peduncle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the cerebellar peduncle exhibits patchy, loose myelination unlike in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum anterior lobe morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced length with failure of Purkinje cells to form a monolayer

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum deep nucleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit abnormal spheroid-like structures or bodies in the neuropil of the deep cerebellar nuclei and vestibular nuclei

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum deep nucleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: deep cerebellar nuclei show some vacuolation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cerebellum growth retardation begins at E12.5 and E14.5 due to decreased cell proliferation, increased ectopic apoptosis (beginning at E14.5), and impaired expansion of cerebellum volume at E14.5, expansion of the intermediate zone is delayed compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cerebellar development is delayed with hypoplasia of the folia and fissure and retarded layer formation until 2 weeks of age at 9 weeks of age, the intercrucial fissure is almost absent; however, other structures are mostly normal

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a large number of granule cells form ectopia along the fusion lines of adjacent folia and at the cerebellar surface underlying the meninges

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum external granule cell layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: incomplete migration at 15 days of age, but normal by 50 days of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum external granule cell layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: upturning of the external granule layer in the most anterior part of the anterobasal cardinal lobe premature halt of the anterior EGL

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum external granule cell layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P0, expression of Ptch, a downstream target of Shh signaling, is reduced in the cerebellum, esp. in the Shh-responsive external granule cell layer (EGL)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum external granule cell layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: missing at E13.5 and P0

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum external granule cell layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: no clear separation of the inner and outer external granule cell layer

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum external granule cell layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: significant delay in granule cell migration during the first 2 weeks of life, but no change in granule cell proliferation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum external granule cell layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice have less compact and disorganized external granule cell layer (EGL) architecture the upper and lower EGL often overlap and many migrating postmitotic granule cells reaching the pial surface at P0, proliferating granule cells are scattered throughout the EGL and also in the cerebellar parenchyma, rather than being primarily confined to the upper EGL as in heterozygous controls at P0, the number of mitotic cells in the EGL is slightly lower; however, at P13 and P15 a significant increase in cell proliferation is detected

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum external granule cell layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: incomplete at E17.5 granule cell progenitors (GCPs) continue to migrate from the rhombic lip hypertrophy of the ventricular zone and EGL due to reduced proliferation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum external granule cell layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: an external granule cell layer is present at postnatal day (P) 17 but not at P21 indicating delayed granule cell migration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum fastigial nucleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: edematous regions/lesions in the deep cerebellar fastigial nucleus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum fastigial nucleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: edematous regions/lesions in the deep cerebellar fastigial nucleus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum fissure morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: more profound fissure delimiting future lobes II and III

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum lobule morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: edematous regions/lesions in the cerebellar lobes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum lobule morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: edematous regions/lesions in the cerebellar lobes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal laminar structure

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: vacuoles appeared in the cerebellar granule cell layer beginning at 2 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cell stratification is disorganized

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P13 (but not at P1), homozygotes exhibit severe degeneration of the cerebellum

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cerebellar defects are not rescued by restoration or complete deletion of n-TRtct5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: severe defects in cerebellar gross morphology proliferating granule cells are scattered throughout the external glial cell layer and in the cerebellar parenchyma but by P0 the number of mitotic cells in the external glial cell layer and cerebrum is slightly lower

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced foliation at P1 and P10

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum vermis lobule I morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: totally missing

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum vermis lobule II morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hypoplasia and abnormalities with a certain degree of variability

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum vermis lobule III morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hypoplasia and abnormalities with a certain degree of variability and abnormality in shape

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebellum vermis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the vermis lacks fissures

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show abnormal cell distribution in the cerebral cortex

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: disrupted architecture due to widespread necrosis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: axonal swelling

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cerebral cortices are highly disorganized by E19.5 some apoptosis is seen in the developing cortices at E13.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduction in cortical surface area at 8 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the ventral-lateral boundaries of the neocortex and palaeocortex terminate in more dorsa positions axonal projections linking opposing cortical hemispheres are altered compared to in wild-type mice axons between the thalamus and cortex are more highly represented than in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: vacuoles appeared in layers 3 and 4 of the cerebral cortex beginning at 2 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: by P18, homozygotes display a dramatic reduction in cerebral cortex size; however, all cortical layers are normally present

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a 7% decrease of cortical volume is noted at P80

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cerebral cortex is smaller and thinner than in controls at P0, anterior-posterior (A-P) length of the cerebral cortex is shorter than in controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cerebral cortex morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal cochlear hair cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 1 and 3 months, vacuole-like spaces replace the afferent terminals of the inner radial nerves while efferent inner spiral fibers appear intact at 1 and 3 months, edematous-appearing extracellular spaces are noted between the IHC and supporting cells; the cytoplasm in the base of IHCs consists of numerous small vesicles infiltrated with mitochondria and short profiles of cisternae in contrast, no major pathological changes are seen in mutant OHCs or stria vascularis at 1 or 3 months all homozygotes (6 of 6) exhibit excitotoxic pathologies of afferent dendrites under the IHCs compared with 4 of 9 in wild-type mice homozygotes show a significantly higher number of swollen dendritic terminals per IHC region relative to wild-type mice; only  type I ganglion neurons are involved

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal complement pathway

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal copper homeostasis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ectoderm development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: loss of columnar epithelial shape multiple layers minimal intercellular spaces normal tight junctions, adherens junctions, and desmosomes apically but not elsewhere basement membrane barely detectable

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ectoplacental cone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ectoplacental cone does not appear vascularized

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ectoplasmic specialization morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the structure of apical ectoplasmic specialization is disrupted

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ectoplasmic specialization morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: testis has abnormalities in the specialized junctional structures of the Sertoli cells, the ectoplasmic specializations, showing unusual vesicular structures in the actin filament layers of the ectoplasmic specializations

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal effector T cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit an increase in the proportion of activated effector T cells and a decrease in the proportion of naive cells in the spleen and lymph nodes compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal effector T cell number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following subcutaneous challenge with FLUAD in 20 month old mice, mice exhibit a 2-fold increase in CD62L-CD44+ T effector cells with a decrease in CD62L+CD44- naive T cells compared with control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal efferent ductules of testis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P3, the number of proliferating (BrdU-labeled) cells is significantly reduced in the epithelium of mutant efferent ducts at the onset of puberty (~3 weeks), all homozygotes exhibit severely hypoplastic and less convoluted efferent ducts relative to wild-type mice at the proximal region (close to the testis), mutant ducts are dilated, their lumina are filled with sperm cells, and immune cell granulomas infiltrate the lumina and surrounding mesenchyme tissue, blocking the transit of sperm and testicular fluid at ~3 weeks, the duct diameter is severely reduced in adult homozygotes, certain epithelial characteristics of the ducts, such as cell height and pseudo-stratification, display a strong variation at the proximal region relative to wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal egg activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ovulated eggs show spontaneous escape from MII arrest, reduced MPF and MAPK activities, and aberrant progression to haploid pronuclear, metaphase III, and anaphase/telophase III stages, similar to normal ovulated eggs after chemical activation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal elbow joint morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: dilated joint spaces and hyperplastic synovium in the elbows found at 11 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal embryonic erythropoiesis

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fetal liver erythropoiesis at E11.5 and E12.5 shows altered proportions of the different developing erythroid populations, in particular within the mature Ter119+ compartment fetal livers show a modest decrease in proerythroblast abundance and an increase in presence of small terminally differentiated red cells early enucleating cells are more abundantly present in fetal livers while percentage of small and enucleated erythrocytes is reduced indicating a partial differentiation block at the erythroblast stage, before enucleation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal embryonic hematopoiesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E13.5, hematopoietic precursors are present in reduced numbers

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: neuroectoderm is hypertrophic at E8.5

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormalities are seen in mutant embryos beginning at E7.5, when apoptotic cells are detectable in the embryo proper by E8.5, mutant embryos show growth arrest and considerable apoptotic cell death in the embryo proper by E9.5-E10, 50% of the mutant embryos are undergoing resorbtion, with the remainder showing severe abnormalites

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal embryonic tissue morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormalities are seen in mutant embryos beginning at 10.5 dpc, when apoptotic cells are detectable in the embryo proper by 10.5 dpc, mutant embryos show growth retardation and a wide range of developmental dysmorphology, and considerable apoptotic cell death in the embryo proper compared to controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal embryonic tissue morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E6.0, most mutant embryos consist of extraembryonic tissue

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal embryonic tissue morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal emotion/affect behavior

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal emotion/affect behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice are very submissive and rarely vocalize in response to stress unlike wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal emotion/affect behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show a deficiency in novel position recognition in the place/position recognition test, with reduced exploration time and preference index of the novel position

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enamel development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit amelogenesis dysregulation in incisors apical bud regions from 6-week-old mandible incisors appear to be reduced, and in particular, the transit-amplifying (TA) zone seems to have disappeared epithelial cells in the TA zone of the apical bud region are transformed into secretory ameloblasts in incisors the initiation of enamel matrix secretion is shifted to the apical bud region in incisors, while the initiation of secretion starts in secretory stage ameloblasts in wild-type incisors ectopic atypical enamel matrix deposition without underlying dentin formation is seen in 40-50% of mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enamel mineralization
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in the maturation stage, severe hypomineralization is seen in the incisor enamel eosinophilic staining of the enamel space in incisors indicates that the degradation and absorption of enamel matrix proteins are not preformed properly by incisor ameloblasts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enamel morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: enamel opacity is increased in mandibular incisors 6-week-old mice show reduced enamel hardness enamel of the maxillary incisors is peeling off at 18 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enamel rod pattern
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: enamel of developing incisors contains a collapsed enamel rod arrangement in the inner enamel, specifically in the area adjacent to the outer enamel

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal endocardium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P5, homozygotes exhibit thickening of the endocardium of the left atrium and left ventricle, with more elastin fibers and collagen fibers relative to heterozygous mutant mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal endochondral bone ossification
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit premature obliteration of growth plates at the sites of endochondral ossification

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal endochondral bone ossification
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impaired

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal endocytosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: enhanced endocytic clearance of amyloid beta 1-42 oligomers and 10 kDa dextran in macrophages and microglia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal endoderm development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal endoderm development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tight intercellular contacts between endoderm cells no basement membrane

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal endoderm development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal endolymphatic duct morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal endometrium morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal energy homeostasis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enteric neural crest cell migration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in conditional mutants from E11.5, enteric neural crest cells show a delay in colonization of the gut; difference in distance traveled by cells in mutants and controls increases with time neural crest cells from mutants fail to invade the hindgut, leading to an aganglionosis of the descending colon after birth when transplanted into wild-type mice, enteric neural crest cells only migrate 66.5% of the distance that wild-type cells migrate

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enteric neural crest cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: enteric neural crest cells exhibit an abnormal association with neuronal processes beginning at E12.5, enteric neural crest cells exhibit increased aggregation and form abnormal clusters that are depend on calcium mechanisms in culture, enteric neural crest cells form aggregates instead of forming scattered neuronal networks as do wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enteric neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in mutants a severe alteration of the neuronal network rostral to the migratory front in observed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enterocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: IECs (intestinal epithelial cells) have distended endoplasmic reticula, and reduced size and number of secretory granules

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enterocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the intestinal epithelium shows large lipid inclusions within the villous enterocytes that are not seen in controls the intestinal microvilli are diminished in size and poorly formed, indicatiang defective enterocyte differentiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enterocyte physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: IECs display loss of homeostatic autophagy

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enterocyte proliferation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decreased in the colon of DSS-treated mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enthesis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: treatment with streptozotocin increased membranous and enchondral ossification of the posterior longitudinal ligament of the cervical spine, esp. in the area of the ligamentous enthesis treatment with streptozotocin also increased the number of alkaline phosphatase positive osteoblast-like mesenchymal cells esp. around the enthesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P2, mutant pups derived from heterozygous matings show a 36.5% reduction in brain cytochrome oxidase activity and a ~75% reduction in skin tyrosinase activity, indicating that the activity of essential cupro-enzymes is significantly diminished maternal deficiency results in a near complete absence of tyrosinase activity in skin tissue extracts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: all molybdenum-dependent enzymes are inactive, as exemplified by xanthine oxidoreductase and sulfite oxidase

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lactate dehydrogenase activity in the brain and heart is increased 2- to 3-fold with corresponding increase in lactate concentration compared to in wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: upon UV irradiation, mutant MEFs (mouse embryonic fibroblasts) show decreased JNK activity compared to wild-type or Mapk8-null MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E4.5, mutant emrbyos show decreased levels of ornithine decarboxylase 1 (Odc1) expression in the epiblast, suggesting inability to produce putrescine and lack of the end products of the polyamine synthesis pathway

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: citrate synthase activity is significantly reduced in cardiac homogenates, indicating a reduction in cardiac mitochondrial density

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: heterozygotes exhibit significantly higher citrate synthase activities in cardiac homogenates, indicating greater cardiac mitochondrial density

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: stromal cells exhibit elevated MMP-9 activity

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: enzyme activity for degrading ADMA (asymmetrical dimethylarginine) and L-NMMA (N<sup>g</sup>-mono-methyl-L-arginine) is undetectable in homozygous mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: protein kinase C (PKC) activity in mutant lungs and epidermis is higher than in controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E9.5 and E10.5, embryos exhibit significantly less calpain activity than wild-type embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme activity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced levels of arginase activity relative to control liver

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: no membrane bound pantetheinase activity in liver and kidney although cytosolic activity present in liver results in an absence of cysteamine in liver and kidney

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: expression of deoxythymidylate kinase (dTYMK) is decreased by about 3-fold in embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: muscle creatine kinase levels are about 3-fold higher than in wild-type littermates

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: heart shows evidence for an attempted switch to glycolytic ATP generation, with induction of rate-limiting glycolytic enzyme genes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mRNA and protein levels of stearoyl-CoA desaturase 1 (SCD1) are severely reduced in the liver

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 1 month old mutants show CoQ9 levels that are 20% of controls in the brain, 28% in the kidney, 62% in the liver and 35% in the muscle 4 month old mutants show even further reduced levels of CoQ9, levels that are 16% of controls in the brain, 21% in the kidney, 25% in the muscle 6 month old mutants show CoQ9 levels that are 28% of controls in the brain, 14% in the kidney, 68% in the liver, and 20% in the muscle liver of 4 month old mutants has increased CoQ9; 157% of controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal enzyme/coenzyme level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygotes exhibit an elevation of many lysosomal enzymes, including beta-hexosaminidase, beta-galactosidase, alpha-mannosidase, acid phosphatase, aryl sulfatase A, and alpha-fucosidase

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal eosinophil physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal eosinophil physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal eosinophil physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: eosinophil chemotaxis towards eotaxin is increased

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal eosinophil physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: eosinophil recruitment to the lungs is enhanced when challenged with antigen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epicardium development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epidermal lamellar body morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epidermal lamellar body morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lamellar membrane structures in stratum corneum are shortened, distorted, and replaced by incompletely processed, lamellar body-derived materials most lamellar bodies in the stratum granulosum layer of the epidermis display abnormalities in size and/or internal contents, indicating an abnormality in lamellar body formation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epidermal layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mild spongiosis (edema) of the epidermis is seen occasionally

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epidermal layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: intracellular edema in the epidermis neutrophil accumulation in superficial layers of epidermis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epidermal layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: epidermal proliferation is inhibited, however a spatial and temporal program of terminal differentiation does occur

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epidermal layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: less affected than in Itgb1<sup>tm1Ref</sup>/Itgb1<sup>tm1Ref</sup> Tg(KRT1-5-cre)5132Jlj mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epidermal layer morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: less affected than in Itgb1<sup>tm1Ref</sup>/Itgb1<sup>tm1Ref</sup> Tg(KRT1-5-cre)5132Jlj mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epidermal melanocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: under non-tumorigenic conditions, newborn (P0) mice show a significant increase in interfollicular melanocytes in back skin relative to control mice P-cadherin-positive clusters are enlarged in interfollicular epidermis, with frequent localization of melanocytes to these compartments

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epidermis stratum corneum morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epidermis stratum corneum morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epididymis morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epididymis morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epididymis morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epididymis morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epididymis morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal epididymis morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal glucose homeostasis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: glucose turnover rate in the basal state is reduced by 20%

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal glucose homeostasis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice fed a high-fat diet retain their glucose tolerance and insulin sensitivity unlike similarly treated wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal glucose homeostasis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased glucose clearance through GLUT4 in skeletal muscle and white adipose tissue

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal glucose homeostasis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following reperfusion of an ischemic heart ex vivo, glucose oxidation to produce ATP is increased 50% compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal glucose homeostasis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: insulin-stimulated whole-body glucose turnover is increased 40% compared to in similarly treated wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal glucose homeostasis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: resistance to development of diabetes and hyperglycemia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal glycogen homeostasis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal gonial bone morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal granulocyte differentiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal granulosa cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal gustatory papilla taste bud morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal gustatory system morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: gustatory innervation is disrupted, while lingual somatosensory innervation is intact

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal gut-associated lymphoid tissue morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: number of intestinal lymphoid follicles is decreased

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal habituation to a new environment
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit impaired habituation to a novel environment

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hair cycle

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hair cycle anagen phase

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hair follicle development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hair follicle development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hair follicle keratinocytes fail to remodel basement membrane and invaginate into the dermis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hair follicle development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hair follicle melanocyte morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hair follicle morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hair shedding
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased shedding

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hair shedding
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at necropsy (15.9 weeks of age), mice fed a high-fat diet exhibit premature separation of the club hair

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hallux morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal head morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal head morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal head morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal head shape

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal head skin morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: expression analysis in cardiomyocytes indicates disruption of sarcomere structure and an inhibition of cardiomyocyte maturation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: unlike in wild-type mice, the typical epicardial progenitor cell cysts are not detected at E9.5 to E10.5 and the myocardium is no covered with a single layer of flat cells at E10.5 to E11.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: defective right ventricle, right atrium, and outflow tract with smaller left ventricle at E11.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: transcriptome analysis shows altered transcriptional networks in both atria and ventricles at P3 at E13.5, hearts show extracellular matrix (ECM) remodeling, as indicated by increased expression of Fn1 (fibronectin 1) and Lamb3 (laminin, beta 3) at E13.5, surface expression of Jag1 (jagged 1) on myocardial (Vcam1+) cells is reduced, leading to altered Notch1 signaling and heart development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E7.5, homozygotes display a poorly developed primitive heart structure

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E10.5, embryos have an abnormally patterned heart with an uncharacteristic, straight morphology to the region between the atria and ventricles

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: defects in heart formation that are similar to in Bmp2tm1.1Jfm homozygotes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E8.5 and E9.5, 2 of 12 homozygotes display no signs of heart development, despite an apparently normal amnion/chorion formation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: gelatinase activity in the mutant hearts is greatly diminished, particularly in the muscular component of the IVS and the valvular leaflets where defects are observed gelatinase deficiency may compromise the matrix remodeling process that is crucial for fusion of the IVS and AV cushion tissue

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hearts are smaller and immature, especially the ventricle region, compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart echocardiography feature

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart left ventricle morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart left ventricle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: left ventricular volume is higher

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart left ventricle morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart left ventricle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following aortic banding, left ventricular end-diastolic dimension is greater than in similarly treated wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart left ventricle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following thoracic aorta constriction, mice exhibit increased left ventricular end-diastolic dimension compared with control mice aged mice exhibit left ventricular posterior wall thickness compared with control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart looping

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart looping
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ~20% of homozygotes show incomplete cardiac looping (tuba rectae)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice die shortly after birth due to severe cardiac malformation

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: regions of epicardial detachment are noted around midgestation at E13.5 and later, mutants have fewer Tcf21-positive interstitial cells with no significant changes in apoptosis or cell proliferation, suggesting defective migration of epicardial cells into the myocardium (epicardial EMT defects) epicardial-derived cells form coronary vascular smooth muscle cells but do not form cardiac fibroblasts; this leads to extracellular matrix (ECM) deficiencies in mutant hearts (lower concentrations of some ECM proteins)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased connective tissue at 16 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased connective tissue at 16 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in 10% of mice at E9.5 and P0

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: severe heart defects in all homozygous mutant and ~10% of heterozygous E9.5 embryos and neonates

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hearts exhibit extracellular matrix accumulation at E12.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: posterior wall thickness is decreased in male mice compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: no beating heart in around 50% of embryos at age E9.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E10.5, embryos show varying degrees of abnormal cardiac morphogenesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: atrial and ventricular walls are thin heart abnormalities are seen in 70% of mice at 1 day and appear to correlate with mice exhibiting postnatal lethality, suggesting that the lethality is due to heart defects

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal heart morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increase in splenic hematopoietic progenitors with a concurrent decrease of hematopoietic progenitors in the bone marrow

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: colony formation in long term culture experiments is severely impaired reflecting a defect in hematopoietic stem cell function competitive repopulation assays suggest a defect in hematopoietic stem cell self renewal the proportion of cells in G0 is reduced suggesting a defect in quiescence maintenance reactive oxygen species are elevated colony formation in short term cultures is reduced for cells from aged mice but not for cells from young mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: BMPCs show decreased colony formation and NO levels

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced colony formation ability of long-term hematopoietic stem cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hematopoietic stem cells transplanted into irradiated recipient mice exhibit increased susceptibility to IMQ-induced psoriasis compared with control cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hematopoietic progenitors exhibit increased serial replating capacity compared with control cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hematopoietic progenitors exhibit increased serial replating capacity compared with control cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased proliferation and altered differentiation potential in vitro

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic stem cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bone marrow progenitor cells show elevated cell death, apoptosis, and G2-M phase accumulation at baseline and upon Mitomycin C treatment

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hematopoietic system physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hemoglobin

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal hippocampal mossy fiber morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the characteristic lamination pattern of mossy fibers emanating from the dentate gyrus is altered; at rostral levels, mossy fibers fail to bifurcate and prematurely invade the stratum pyramidale, forming thick, fasciculated bundles that aberrantly navigate between CA3 somata more caudally, the suprapyramidal bundle is discernable but appears less compact and reduced in width, especially in CA3c the infrapyramidal bundle is absent or misplaced in the stratum pyramidale CB+ mossy fiber density in the stratum pyramidale of CA3 is increased the length of both the suprapyramidal bundle and infrapyramidal bundle and the distance between them are decreased

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: enhanced hepatic VLDL-TG secretion contributing to impaired plasma lipid clearance following acute lipid load

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: livers show increased 4-Hydroxy-2-nonenal staining indicating increased oxidative stress increased autophagy and mitophagy in the liver

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: absent or minimal hepatic lipidosis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: livers exhibit increased lipid and protein oxidation indicating mild oxidative stress compared with wild-type livers

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after chronic CCl4-induced liver injury, mice show an exacerbated promoter switch from P1-driven to P2-driven Hnf4a (hepatic nuclear factor 4, alpha) expression, with greater downregulation of Hnf4a P1 mRNA expression and HNF4alpha1 protein isoform expression and a more robust induction of Hnf4a P2 mRNA and protein isoforms than wild-type controls chronically CCl4-injured livers show higher Cyp2e1 mRNA levels, increased DNA damage, and higher accumulation of IgG, CYP2E1, and nitrosylated protein (3-nitrotyrosine) levels than CCl4-injured wild-type livers, consistent with aggravated liver damage and hepatic dedifferentiation after acute APAP-induced liver injury, mRNA expression of Hnf4a P1 isoforms is reduced at 6h while HNF4alpha1 protein isoform expression is depleted at 12 h after APAP treatment; these responses are paralleled by decreased protein levels of USP10 and G3BP1, increased expression of CYP2E1, and enhanced protein nitration, ROS production, heme-oxygenase-1 expression, and TP53 stabilization

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: liver uptake of HDL cholesterol ester is reduced, but uptake in other tissues if unaffected

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: expression analysis in fostered pups indicates a defect in liver adaptation to weaning

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: expression analysis in fostered pups indicates a defect in liver adaptation to weaning that is independent of maternal genotype application of Vaseline or latex to the mitigate the skin barrier defect almost completely rescues liver adaptation to weaning

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: liver damage due to ConA treatment regardless of pretreatment with Il6

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver regeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after partial hepatectomy, livers in mutant mice treated with Dipin to induce DNA damage have a considerably lower DNA labeling index compared to wild-type-Dipin PH livers

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver regeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following liver injury, hepatocytes from mutants treated with an adenoviral cre, exhibit abnormal mitosis with misaligned, centrophilic chromosomes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver regeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: maximal DNA synthesis in hepatocytes after partial hepatectomy and    lipopolysaccharide treatment is reduced relative to controls 10% of cells as compared to 30% of cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver regeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: maximal DNA synthesis in hepatocytes after partial hepatectomy and lipopolysaccharide treatment is reduced relative to controls 20% of cells as compared to 30% of cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver regeneration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: maximal DNA synthesis in hepatocytes after partial hepatectomy occurs after about 48 hours hepatocyte growth factor has no effect on hepatocyte proliferation unless administered with Il6

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver sinusoid morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 4 months, pIpC-treated mice exhibit liver sinusoids with a lymphoid and trilineage myeloid elements and some focused perivascular infiltrations unlike control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver sinusoidal endothelial cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a few sinusoidal endothelial cells contain fine intracytoplasmic vacuoles

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver vasculature morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: persistent absence of hepatic arteries

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver vasculature morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: number and size of vessels is increased as compared to controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal liver vasculature morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice from mothers on the acceleration diet during pregnancy and also fed this diet exhibit mineralized blood vessels in the liver, but no mineralization in the liver parenchyma

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: show a significant decrease in wheel-running activity 2 hours after onset of the dark period for a duration of 6 hours, however see no differences from wild-type in circadian rhythmicity or lcomotor activity during the subjective day, in performance in the rotarod or Morris water maze, and in cued or contextual fear conditioning

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduction in the amount of spontaneous movement is initial sign of abnormalities

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impaired locomotion that worsens with age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased time spent in the center area during a 10 minute period in and open field; however, overall locomotor activity in an open field is not different from wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit bursts of hyperactivity followed by periods of inactivity that were longer than normal

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor activation
