OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygotes that survive more than 48 hours display  periods of hyperactivity followed by inactivity

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor activation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: slightly increased time spent in the center in an open field test

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in the first segment of the open field assessment (0-300 seconds), mutants make more entries into the center zone compared to wild-type mice, spend more time in the center and exhibit more frequent freezing bouts and increased amount of time spent freezing

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: severe locomotor deficiencies deficiencies become more severe after 8 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: severe locomotor deficiencies deficiencies become more severe after 8 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: significantly reduced latency to fall from rotating rod in accelerating Rotarod tests stayed almost still with overstretched unbalanced hind limbs when hung by their tails at age 6 months

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following alcohol withdrawal, mutant mice show unaltered exploratory behavior in light/dark box test, unlike wild-type that show decreased locomotor activity

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal locomotor ability

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced total X-axis beam breaks per 24h at age 11-12 weeks, irrespective of temperature

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced total X-axis beam breaks per 24h at age 17-18 weeks, irrespective of temperature

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor circadian rhythm
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygotes show elevated locomotor activity in a several-hour period preceding the light-to-dark transition (pre-dusk activity)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor circadian rhythm
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: under a 12 h light and 12 h dark (LD) cycle, the total daily wheel-running activity of some mutants is lower than that of wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor coordination
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutants cannot walk  for an extended time on a straight path

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor coordination
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a few homozygotes nearing wean age are found to roll over and over in a struggle to right themselves

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor coordination
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: although motor coordination in younger mice appears normal, after 12 months of age the gait becomes uncoordinated with an increased side-to-side body sway and increased difficulty in rearing and climbing

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor coordination
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 12 months, mice exhibit less diagonal distance between front and hind limbs than Tg(Lrrk2)6Yue mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal locomotor coordination
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal walking

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone diaphysis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P0, the central ossified diaphysis is reduced compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone diaphysis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: well-formed marrow space and diaphysis with scattered thin spicules of primary trabecular bone does not occur until E17.5 compared to E16.5 for controls eccentric thickening of the diaphyseal cortex also occurs during development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone epiphyseal plate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P37, slight lesions are found in the long bone epiphyseal plate mice exhibit an increase in the length of growth plate length at the costochondral junction at P1 that decreases with age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone epiphyseal plate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P10, the growth plate has altered columnar organization and is discontinuous across the width of the skeletal elements with continuous primary and secondary ossification centers in areas where the growth plate is missing at P15, growth plate structure is completely abrogated with ossification centers merged and the distance from the articular surface to the trabecular bone is reduced at P30, growth plates in the long bones are missing

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone epiphyseal plate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: slightly disorganized

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone epiphyseal plate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: growth plates are smaller than in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone epiphyseal plate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E17.5, mice exhibit reductions of the half tibia length (17.2% reduction), the distance between the growth plate and the middle of diaphysis (43.2% reduction), the length of the bone marrow zone (45% reduction) and the length of the hypertrophic zone (15% reduction) compared to wild-type mice at E17.5, the resting zone is increased in length by 10% compared to wild-type mice the growth plate is severely disorganized with large and round-shaped chondrocytes failing to glide over each other and form columns as in wild-type mice at 6 weeks of age, growth plates are completely disorganized and broadened

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone epiphyseal plate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E17.5, mice exhibit reductions of the half tibia length (17.2% reduction), the distance between the growth plate and the middle of diaphysis (43.2% reduction), the length of the bone marrow zone (45% reduction) and the length of the hypertrophic zone (15% reduction) compared to wild-type mice at E17.5, the resting zone is increased in length by 10% compared to wild-type mice the growth plate is severely disorganized with large and round-shaped chondrocytes failing to glide over each other and form columns as in wild-type mice at 6 weeks of age, growth plates are completely disorganized and broadened

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone epiphyseal plate proliferative zone
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P7, the length of the zone of flat proliferating cells is reduced at P7 and P10 fewer cells are undergoing mitosis (pH3+) in the growth plate (86% and 78%, respectively) at P10, columnar alignment of the proliferating cells is lost with abnormal movement of the cells during rotation despite intact polarity of the cells at P15, no mitosis is detected, cells have a round morphology and lack polarity

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone epiphysis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P7, reduction of the epiphysis is due to reduction in the flat chondrocyte regions without a reduction in the length of the hypertrophic zone at P10, the length is reduced; however, the width is increased at P30, the growth plates in the long bones are missing

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone epiphysis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: distal tibia shows enlarged epiphysis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone hypertrophic chondrocyte zone
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P15, hypertrophic cells invade the prehypertrophic zones

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone hypertrophic chondrocyte zone
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E15.5, mice lack an organized hypertrophic zone unlike wild-type mice differentiation of hypertrophic chonndrocytes is incomplete chondrocytes exhibit abnormal mineralization that precludes vascularization of skeletal elements

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone hypertrophic chondrocyte zone
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: by P2 hypertrophic chondrocytes are found in the chondrocostal cartilage of mutants but not in wild-type mice by P8 a mature ossification center is established and the hypertrophic chondrocytes are replace by trabeculated bone

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone hypertrophic chondrocyte zone
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: no hypertrophic chondrocytes are seen at E18.5 in the forelimbs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone hypertrophic chondrocyte zone
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P0, homozygotes display reduced expression levels of specific extracellular matrix components (aggrecan and link protein) within the hypertrophic zone, leading to inferior cartilage mechanical properties

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone hypertrophic chondrocyte zone
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E17.5, mice exhibit 15% reduction in the length of the hypertrophic zone compared to wild-type mice while the hyperproliferative zone is reduced, the prehyperproliferative zone is increased

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone hypertrophic chondrocyte zone
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E17.5, mice exhibit 15% reduction in the length of the hypertrophic zone compared to wild-type mice while the hyperproliferative zone is reduced, the prehyperproliferative zone is increased

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone metaphysis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit a slight widening of lateral length at the metaphyses of distal femurs and proximal tibiae unlike in wild-type mice at 10, 18, and 37 days, mice exhibit an accumulation of unresorbed endochondral trabeculae unlike in wild-type mice metaphyseal borders are irregular

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone metaphysis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: distal tibia shows enlarged metaphysis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone metaphysis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fewer trabeculas in the metaphyseal regions

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormalities occur distal to the humerus and femur

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: layered appearance

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at birth, homozygotes display kinks in the radius, ulna, tibia and fibula at E14.5, mutant long bones are already bent near the junction between hypertrophic and nonhypertrophic cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: long bones are sclerotic, but to a much lesser extent than in homozygous Gsub<sup>tm1Sly</sup> mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: long bones are sclerotic, but to a much lesser extent than in homozygous Gsub<sup>tm1Sly</sup> mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long-term depression
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutants exhibit enhanced long-term depression in the striatum mutants exhibit enhanced hippocampal metabotropic glutamate receptor dependent (mGluR)-long-term depression treatment with 4DGI-1, an inhibitor of Eif4e-Eif4g interactions, normalizes the enhanced striatal long term depression

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long-term potentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: long term potentiation by high frequency stimulation enhanced while it was reduced or absent at low frequency reduced neurotransmitter release effect due to actin perturbation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long-term potentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a single tetanus induces a robust and sustained late LTP unlike in wild-type mice where a single tetanus induces early LTP after repeated tetanic stimulation (4 trains at 100 Hz) the duration of late LTP is reduced, returning to baseline within 3 hours

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long-term spatial reference memory
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice do not spend more time in the goal zone as seen in wild-type mice at 48 hours following the final training session in the Morris water maze, indicating impaired long-term memory during the memory test of the Y-maze, mice take longer to locate the platform, indicating impaired long-term memory

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long-term spatial reference memory
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice injected with an adenovirus expressing cre recombinase into the bilateral dorsal hippocampus exhibit impaired memory in the Morris water maze probe test

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long-term spatial reference memory
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show a longer time to find the hidden platform and a shorter time of staying in the target quadrant in the Morris water maze test, with normal swimming speed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long-term spatial reference memory
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit impaired long term memory in a novel recognition, water maze, and passive avoidance assay compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal long-term spatial reference memory
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: strong impairment in spatial pattern separation in the similar location recognition (SLR) test

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal loop of Henle ascending limb thick segment morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: dilated to a lesser extent than collecting tubules

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lower incisor morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 18 weeks, mice have opaque mandibular incisors with chalky surfaces compared to transparent and glossy incisors in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lumbar dorsal root ganglion morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: numerous DRG neurons appear shrunken and irregular and some show signs of chromatolysis, with flattened nuclei at 15 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: most lungs are developmentally arrested around the early saccular stage since air saccules fail to form marker analysis indicates impaired proximal and distal epithelial cell differentiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: postnatal expansion of lungs failed to occur

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygotes display impaired distal lung bud epithelium development, as suggested by the reduction of Id2 expression in the growing tip of the branching epithelium

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: perinatal development of terminal airway branches is arrested

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impaired lung maturation at E17.5 with lungs still at the canalicular stage when lungs in wild-type embryos have reached the saccular stage number and size of small airways and distal airspaces are significantly smaller atE17.5 developmental delay correlates to overall embryo size formation and maturation of distal epithelial cells are slightly behind schedule at E17.5 delay in lung development is detectable at E12.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: delayed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit enhanced TGF-beta signaling and impaired distal airspace septation at P7, dysregulation of TGF-beta activation and signaling results in increased apoptosis, but normal cell proliferation, in the developing lung treatment with TGF-beta neutralizing antibody attenuates apoptosis and improves alveolar septation in vivo

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5, mutant lungs appear to be arrested at the canalicular stage of lung development immunostaining for PDGFB, its receptor and IGF1, are markedly attenuated, while the normal proximal-to-distal increasing TTF1 gradient is lost, indicating abnormal distribution and abundance of cell cycle modulators involved in lung development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung endothelial cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: total dolichol levels in lung endothelial cells treated with an adenovirus-expressing cre (Ad-Cre) recombinase are reduced lung endothelial cells show reduced glycosylation of VEGFR2, CD31, and VE-cad and increased ER stress markers dolichol phosphate supplementation in the media of lung endothelial cell cultures increases the levels of glycosylated endothelial proteins, indicating rescue of glycosylation defects

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung endothelial cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lung endothelial cells exposed to disturbed blood flow and laminar blood flow showed less activation evidenced by markedly decreased  anti-VCAM-1 staining

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung endothelial cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: no activation in isolated mouse lung endothelial cells (MLECs) after exposure to inflammatory conditions

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung epithelium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E14.5, the mutant lung epithelium is improperly aligned and shows a multilayered and/or disorganized morphology, unlike the single layer of uniformly aligned columnar epithelium seen in wild-type lungs at E14.5, mutant lung epithelial cells are highly disorganized and randomly orientated with either small or no lumina, and not readily distinguishable from surrounding mesenchyme by DAPI labeling Celsr1<sup>Crsh</sup> airways appeared more severely affected than Vangl2<sup>Lp</sup> airways

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung epithelium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P0, an absolute increase in bronchiolar epithelium indicates a defect in epithelial cell fate specification/differentiation numbers of proximal versus distal cell types are significantly greater than in wild-type, indicating impaired proximodistal differentiation of the airway epithelium

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung epithelium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the airway epithelium remains multi-layered unlike in wild-type embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung epithelium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E16.5, bronchiolar epithelium morphogenesis is normal but terminal bud epithelium appears degenerated

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung interstitium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: perivascular and peribronchiolar connective tissues of lung show similar, but less conspicuous infiltrations

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung interstitium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: thickened parenchymal septa

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung lobe morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5, mutant lung lobes are visibly misshapen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung lobe morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: irregularly shaped at E17.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E14.5 and E18.5, mutant lungs show cytokeletal defects and disordered epithelial airways with no apparent  disruption of adherens junctions

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 3 months, pulmonary alterations in mice on a 129/Sv congenic background are stronger than in mice on a C57BL/6 congenic background mice on a congenic 129/Sv background exhibit wide clinical variability

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: crystals are seen in the lungs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: proximal mucinous metaplasia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung position or orientation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lung isomerism

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung saccule morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5, mutant lungs show atypical saccular structure with no evidence of septation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung vasculature morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at birth, surface vasculature of lungs is abnormal at P0, capillaries are dilated and are not in direct apposition to airways

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung vasculature morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after tamoxifen treatment the size and number of blood vessels in the lung is increased

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung vasculature morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: pulmonary vessels occasionally appear distended and hyalinized

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lung vasculature morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bronchiolar arteries thickened, tortuous, with smooth muscle cell hyperplasia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymph circulation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 20 of 25 heterozygotes exhibit lymph reflux from the cisterna chyli into dilated lymphatic channels within the hepatic hilum, mesentery, mesenteric lymph nodes and the intestinal wall through incompetent interlymphangion valves

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymph circulation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: dye injected into the hind foot pad fails to be transported into deeper lymphatic vessels

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymph circulation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mesenteric lymphatic vessels appear diffuse suggesting that they are leaky and dysfunctional

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymph node cell ratio
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: despite a reduction in number, the percentage of CD8+ T cells in the lymph nodes tends to increase compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymph node germinal center morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: aging mice exhibit increased germinal centers in lymph nodes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymph node morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at >28 weeks of age, heavily laden melanocytes are present in draining lymph nodes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymph organ development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E12.5, jugular lymph sacs are dilated

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphangiogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lymphangiogenic sprouting is disrupted

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphangiogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit disrupted lymph sac formation and lymphatic growth

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphangiogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice lack lymphatic vessel growth towards the dorsal central line with few enlarged lymphatic vessels around the forelimb skin

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphatic vessel morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: presence of peripheral edema at E14.5 suggests altered embryonic lymphatic vessel development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphatic vessel morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lymphatic vessels in the intestinal submucosa are enlarged lymphatic vessels are mostly absent from the skin with only a few enlarged cutaneous vessels present; however, viral overexpression of Flt4 ligand can induce lymphatic vessel development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphatic vessel morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: only some remnants of lymphatic vessels are present in the skin at E17.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphatic vessel morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: blood-filled lymphatic vessels in the intestine, heart, diaphragm, and skin in adult lymphatic vessels of homozygous mutants are blood-filled by mid-gestation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphatic vessel morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: blood-filled lymphatic vessels in the intestine, heart, diaphragm, and skin in adult lymphatic vessels of homozygous mutants are blood-filled by mid-gestation occasional fusion between blood and lymphatic vessels

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphocyte cell number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fraction of B and T cells in spleen is significantly decreased but in lymph nodes these numbers are increased

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: exhibit accelerated apoptosis of lymphocytes lymphocyte development initially appears normal, however lymphocytes from spleen or thymus lose the differentiated B220+/IgM+ B cell or CD4+/CD8+ T cell subpopulation, respectively

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced B to T cell ratios in the peripheral blood

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced B to T cell ratios in the peripheral blood

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphocyte physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit a reduced number of IFN-gamma+ group 1 innate lymphoid cells (ILC1s) after S. typhimurium infection mice show a decreased number of group 2 innate lymphoid cells (ILC2s) in the lung and a reduced number of IL-5 and IL-13 secreting ILC2s in the lung after papain challenge

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphocyte physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: pre-T cells cultured without cytokines or with ionomycin or taxol survive 10 to 30 times better than wild-type cells pre-T cells are resistant to dexamethasone or gamma-irradiation induced cell death but not to phorbol 12-myristate 13-acetate (PMA) or Fas ligand induced cell death pre-B cells are also resistant to cell death induced by cytokine withdrawal, ionomycin, taxol, and dexamethasone but display sensitivity to cell death similar to wild-type following gamma irradiation or exposure to PMA or Fas ligand

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphocyte physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: pre-T cells cultured without cytokines or with ionomycin or taxol survive better than wild-type cells but not as well as homozygous cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphocyte physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: survival of mature resting T and B cells in the absence of cytokines is improved compared to wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphocyte physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: survival of mature resting T and B cells in the absence of cytokines is impaired compared to wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphocyte physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impairment in the ability to produce IFNG in response to Con A stimulation IL12 treatment can rescue the impairment in IFNG production

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lymphopoiesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: frequencies of alpha-lymphoid progenitors, common helper innate lymphoid cell progenitors (CHILPs), and innate lymphoid cell precursors (ILCPs) are reduced in the small intestine and liver, ILC2s in the small intestine and lung, and ILC3s in the small intestine mutant common lymphoid progenitors (CLPs) engrafted into Rag1/Il2rg null recipients produce fewer numbers of innate lymphoid cells (ILCs) differentiation ability of alpha4Beta7+ CLPs in culture is suppressed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: autolysosomes (degrading autophagic vacuoles) absent

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced number of LysoTracker-positive organelles and reduced fluorescence of positive organelles in cortical neurons reduction in number LAMP1-positive puncta and reduced overall LAMP1-positive signal in cortical neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant MEFs display accumulation of autolysosomes (defined as vesicles labeled for both Lamp1 and p62) and decreased lysosome numbers (defined as Lamp1-positive vesicles that do not co-stain for p62) relative to wild-type MEFs upon induction of autophagy by serum starvation for 6 h, lysosomes are significantly depleted in both wild-type and mutant MEFs; however, after 14 h of starvation, lysosome numbers return to baseline levels only in wild-type while they remain diminished in mutant MEFs lysosome numbers are already reduced in Purkinje cells and cortical motoneurons at 2 months of age, prior to accumulation of autofluorescent material or any signs of neurodegeneration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Sertoli cells show sulfogalactosylglycerolipid (SGG) accumulation leading to lysosomal swelling and other cellular abnormalities typical of a lysosomal storage disorder at 8 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lysosomal storage disorder

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abundant lysosomal storage in liver, kidney, leptomeningeal cells, cornea, spleen, neurons, and retinal pigment epithelium

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lysosomal storage in liver, kidney, leptomeningeal cells, cornea, spleen, neurons, and retinal pigment epithelium, but to a lesser extent than in homozygous Gsub<sup>tm1Sly</sup> mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lysosomal storage in liver, kidney, leptomeningeal cells, cornea, spleen, neurons, and retinal pigment epithelium, but to a lesser extent than in homozygous Gsub<sup>tm1Sly</sup> mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lysosomal storage disease

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: vacuolar storage in many tissues (lysosomal storage disorder)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lysosomal storage disorder

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: exhibit lysomal storage in visceral tissues, brain and cornea, however mice are viable, fertile, and appear healthy up to 12 months of age unlike humans with mutations of the orthologous gene, mice do not display any skeletal abnormalities

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased lysosomal mass in mouse embryonic fibroblasts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced number of LysoTracker-positive organelles and reduced fluorescence of positive organelles in cortical neurons increased pH in cortical neurons reduction in number LAMP1-positive puncta and reduced overall LAMP1-positive signal in cortical neurons significant reduction in processing of exogenous DQ-BSA and Dextran-AF594 in cortical neurons increased accumulation of cytosolic granules in in cortical neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant MEFs  show an increased number of autolysosomes as well as increased levels of LC3-II (the lipidated form of LC3 recruited to autophagosomal membranes) relative to wild-type MEFs, indicating impaired autolysosomal clearance in mutant MEFs, LC3-II levels are further increased upon treatment with bafilomycin A1, which inhibits autolysosome acidification and autolysosomal degradation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal lysosome physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: accumulation of disaccharide is seen in some but not all visceral organs and in the nervous system

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage apoptosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bone marrow-derived macrophages are resistant to LPS- or S. typhimurium-induced pyroptosis unlike wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage apoptosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bone marrow-derived macrophages are resistant to LPS- or S. typhimurium-induced pyroptosis unlike wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage apoptosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: resist LPS-induced pyroptosis in bone marrow-derived macrophages

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: macrophages are sites of storage of glycosaminoglycans (GAGs) which are found at high levels in all tissues examined

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the phagocytic activity of peritoneal macrophages is significantly enhanced

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: macrophages exhibit an acute elevation of proinflammatory cytokines IL-1beta, IL-6, and IP-10, but not IL-10, in response to ingesting dying cells that is not seen in control macrophages

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: macrophage exhibit increased susceptible to infection by the adenoviral vector Ad5-F16-GFP compared with wild-type cells macrophage are moderately susceptible to MCMV infection and increased susceptibility to MCMV infection by intraperitoneal injection compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bone marrow derived and peritoneal macrophages infected with VSV show reduced expression of Ifnb1 and Isg15

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: IL-1beta production by fetal-derived or chimeric-derived macrophages is enhanced to TLR3, TLR4, TLR7 and TLR9 ligands levels of reactive oxygen species is higher in fetal liver-derived macrophages than controls after stimulation with LPS

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: macrophages show impaired clearance of Y. enterocolitica

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: isolated bone-marrow derived and peripheral macrophages do not show induction of IFNalpha, IFNbeta, and Il-6 or activation of NF-kappaB by Sendai virus; response to LPS is normal though

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: macrophage from mice infected with West Nile virus exhibit increased virus replication compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fibrillar beta-amyloid stimulated reactive oxygen species production is reduced 90% compared to in wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fail to produce nitric oxide after stimulation with lipopolysaccharide or IFN-gamma either separately or in combination

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: peritoneal macrophages fail to produce superoxide upon stimulation in vitro with N-formyl-methionyl-leucyl-phenylalanine (fMLP) or phorbol 12-myristate 13-acetate (PMA)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal macrophage physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: peritoneal macrophages produce less Il-6, Il-12p40, TNF alpha, and nitric oxide compared to wild-type cells upon stimulation with interferon gamma and/or LPS

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal magnesium ion homeostasis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decreased in the serum, urine and bone when maintained on a diet with 0.17% magnesium decreased in the bone when maintained on a normal diet decreased in the plasma, erythrocyte and bone when maintained on a magnesium deficient diet

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal magnesium ion homeostasis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit an increase in brain magnesium level compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male germ cell apoptosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in infertile males, a population of early meiotic cells exhibits apoptosis, as indicated by TUNEL analysis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male germ cell apoptosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: slight

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male germ cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: sulfogalactosylglycerolipid (SGG) levels are normal at 5 months but significantly decreased in primary spermatocytes and condensing elongated spermatids at 8 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male meiosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increase in frequency of meiotic recombination during pachytene in spermatocytes as indicated by an increase in the number of MHL1 foci in pachytene spermatocytes and an increase in the number of chiasmata in diakinesis/metaphase I nuclei of spermatocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male meiosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a higher proportion of spermatocytes show an abnormal gamma-H2A.X distribution, indicating the DNA damage response remains active in synapsed homologs of pachytene spermatocytes pachytene spermatocytes show abnormal double-strand DNA break (DSB) repair pachytene and diplotene spermatocytes are reduced indicating developmental retardation of pachytene spermatocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male meiosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: XY body malformation and SYCP3 overloading in pachytene stage spermatocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male meiosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: while spermatocytes undergo programmed double-strand breaks and initial assembly of the synaptonemal complex, the compaction of the XY axes is rarely seen in spermatocytes indicating XY body malformation spermatocytes undergo SYCP3 overloading which becomes evident once homolog synapsis is completed at pachytene and overloaded SYCP3 remains even in metaphase I and anaphase I some chromosomes connected with SYCP3 fail to align at the equatorial plate and are left behind between two centrosomes SYCP3 overloading is biased to the X chromosome in male meiosis and the X chromosomes exhibit an abnormal synapsis state

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male meiosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased frequency of synaptic abnormalities beginning in mid-zygotene

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male meiosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P14, no meiotic cells are found in the testes of tamoxifen-treated mice; only mitotic cells are observed no SYCP3+ or gammaH2AX+ cells are observed in the seminiferous tubules of tamoxifen-treated mice at P14 at P70, chromosome spreads from tamoxifen-treated testes show meiosis defects, including a significant reduction in zygotene and pachytene spermatocytes, defective double-strand DNA repair, and a significant decrease in MLH1 foci in pachytene spermatocytes indicating reduced crossover formation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male meiosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: immunofluorescence staining of meiotic markers showed no SYCP3+ or gammaH2AX+ cells in seminiferous tubules at P8

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal male preputial gland morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: male mice months 18 months of age have enlarged preputial glands with severe duct ectasia, focal hyperplasia, and hyperkeratosis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal malleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in newborns the malleus is misshapen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal malleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the malleus is fused to the incus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland alveolus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: by P18, mutant lobuloalveolar structures are less developed relative to wild-type controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland alveolus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the lumina of mutant mammary alveoli are full of milk and become dilated in the initial postpartum period (postpartum day 5)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: terminal end buds (TEB) in 5 week old females lack well-defined lumens 86.6% of wild-type TEBs have well-defined lumens compared to just 4.4% of controls these TEBs are larger in size and contain an inner cell population that is composed of an unorganized epithelial mass and scattered squamous cell clusters mutant TEBs are associated with 10-fold less apoptosis than controls ducts also have defects in clearing of inner cells at 5 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: whole wild-type mammary glands transplanted into mutant recipient mice show fully developed lobuloalveolar structures and visible milk droplets whereas whole mutant mammary glands transplanted into wild-type recipient mice fail to develop normally

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland duct morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ducts of 5-week old mammary glands lack well defined lumens compared to controls an inner cell population that is composed of an unorganized epithelial mass and scattered squamous cell clusters squamous cell clusters lack adhesion to the epithelial cells of the duct may represent a population of cells undergoing squamous differentiation these squamous cells express keratin and some other epithelial markers at 6-7 weeks, the inner cell population begins dying off in a caspase-independent manner by  8 weeks ducts are hollowed and indistinguishable from wild-type controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland epithelium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: female homozygotes show impaired differentiation of mammary gland epithelium in late pregnancy transplantation of mutant epithelium to wild-type mammary fat pads results in apparently normal epithelial growth, whereas transplantation of wild-type epithelium to mutant fat pads leads to underdeveloped and poorly differentiated epithelium

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland epithelium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the mutant alveolar epithelium appears flattened in the initial postpartum period, unlike in wild-type controls a progressive loss of epithelial cell components is noted at postpartum days 9 and 13 in mutant mammary glands

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland growth during lactation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: on day 1 of lactation ( L1), mutant glands show a ~25% reduction in epithelial structures and a ~60% reduction in luminal expansion

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland growth during lactation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the mammary glands of mutant lactating dams are generally smaller (and less active) than wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland growth during lactation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: starting at day 4 of lactation, alveolar density is reduced and at day 12 alveoli are larger, less organized, and separated by adipocytes reduced numbers of  myoepithelial cells are seen beginning at lactation day 4 and these cells are nearly absent at lactation day 12 massive apoptosis of myoepithelial cells is detected at lactation day 10

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland growth during lactation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: luminal cell proliferation is reduced in mammary glands at day 5 of lactation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland lobule morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 0.5 days after delivery, vacuolation of the lobules of the mammary gland is observed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 9 days after parturition, overall abundance of mammary gland tissue is similar, or even increased, in mutants vs wild-type at days 9 and 13 postpartum, a progressive loss of epithelial cell components and an increase in adipose tissue is observed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 0.5 days after delivery there is an increase in the glandular to adipose tissue ratio

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at lactation day 5, mammary glands have defects in alveolar integrity, with detachment of luminal epithelial cells resulting in an 11-fold increase in luminally shed and bulging cells due to alterations in cell-basement membrane associations the defect in alveolar integrity becomes more pronounced during a second lactation density of the lobular-alveolar structures is decreased at day 5 of the first, and more strongly, the second lactation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland myoepithelium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced numbers of myoepithelial cells are seen beginning at lactation day 4 and these cells are nearly absent at lactation day 12

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland myoepithelium physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: massive apoptosis of myoepithelial cells is detected at lactation day 10

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland myoepithelium physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: myoepithelial cells in mutant mammary tissues show dysfunction

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: injection of oxytocin and/or prolactin does not rescue mortality/failure to thrive of litters tended by homozygous females

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mammary gland sensory innervation pattern
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E13, female mice exhibit very few sensory neurons associated with the mammary gland rudiments unlike wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal manchette disassembly
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in stages I-II, the manchette is abnormally retained, indicating a delay in manchette clearance

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal manchette morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in some spermatids, membranous structures appearing like flat saccules are associated with the manchette some spermatids show a normal manchette associated with a nucleus of an irregular outline

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal manchette morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: starting at step 11, elongating spermatids exhibit an abnormally elongated manchette and a nuclear constriction is observed at the juncture of the groove and perinuclear ring during steps 11-12, MNS1 (meiosis-specific nuclear structural protein 1), a KIF3A-interacting protein, is abnormally concentrated in the manchette

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal manchette perinuclear ring morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: early elongating spermatids (steps 9-11) often show an perinuclear ring that is detached from the nucleus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mandible morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: variable position of the mandible with respect to the skull (excluded from analysis)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mandible morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cleft in the mandible in 25% of embryos at E12.5 mandible is bilaterally smaller and asymmetrical in some embryos at E14.5 and E17.5 proximal elements are absent

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mandibular nerve morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced and appears to have formed ventral to the first arch at E10.5 in some embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal marginal zone B cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: marginal zone B cells are unable to capture TNP-Ficoll, a T cell-independent antigen marginal zone B cells fail to activate NF-kappaB efficiently after stimulation with lipopolysaccharide (LPS)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mast cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: evidence of degranulation of mast cells in the skin

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mast cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: serotonin concentrations in cultured mast cells are lower than in wild-type cells but not as low as in Mitf<sup>Mi</sup> cultured mast cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mast cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: serotonin concentrations in cultured mast cells are lower than in wild-type cells cultured mast cells exhibit no cytotoxicity towards YAC-1 cells unlike wild-type mast cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mast cell physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: highly activated mast cells with defective ATP clearance and enhanced ATP responses

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maternal behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: unlike wild-type females, middle-aged mutant females spend an equal time in the nest during the three lactating stages (day 1, 11, and 21 of lactation)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maternal nurturing
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased incidence of perinatal mortality 28% of pups born die within 48 hours of birth

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maternal nurturing
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: all pups produced by mating female homozygotes with an ICR male die within 4 days due to maternal neglect

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maternal nurturing
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: deficiencies in nurturing behavior

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maternal nurturing
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: exhibit defects in the maternal behavior of nest building and pup retrieval, regardless of exposure to hexanal females exposed to autoclaved chips of Douglas fir that contain about 10-fold greater amount of hexanal, show partially impaired maternal behavior as indicated by decreased time spent in the maternal crouching behavior and the continuous change of the position of the nest after parturition

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maternal nurturing
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: females are more likely to neglect or consume their litters compared to controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mating frequency
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: some homozygous fail to give vaginal plugs with wild-type females

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mature B cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: number of mature IgD<sup>+</sup> IgM<sup>low</sup> recirculating B cells is selectively decreased and have very low levels of cell surface IgD 12% of normal levels of IgD and 30% of normal IgM on the cell surface

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maxilla morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: laterally displaced at E17.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maxilla morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: rough appearance around the roots of damaged upper incisors sclerosis in the maxillary area

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maxillary nerve morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: disorganized and missing at E10.5 in some embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maxillary zygomatic process morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the zygomatic process of the maxilla is thicker and continues to be thick halfway into the zygomatic bone compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal maxillary zygomatic process morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: smaller zygomatic process of the maxilla

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mechanical nociception
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit increased reflex withdrawal thresholds in the von Frey test of mechanical pain compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mechanical nociception
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit increased reflex withdrawal thresholds in the von Frey test of mechanical pain compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mechanoreceptor morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit fewer IB4-binding neurons (non-peptidergic nociceptor neurons) in the dorsal root ganglia than in wild-type mice IB4-binding axons extend deeper into the dorsal horn of the spinal cord than in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal medium spiny neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: adult mice show a 17% decrease in the number of nuclei labeling with CTIP2, a marker of medium spiny neurons, in the dorsal striatum; however, the density of medium spiny neurons is not changed the number of primary dendrites, dendritic branch points or nodes, dendritic tips, and total length are decreased in striatal medium spiny neurons; however, mean dendritic length is not changed Sholl analysis revealed reduced cumulative dendritic length and decreased Sholl intersections spine density is reduced by ~15%

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal medium spiny neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the cross-sectional area of medium spiny neuron soma is reduced by 25% and the diameter of all portions of the dendritic tree is reduced by about 40% compared to wild-type mice with spine density reduced by 30-40% at every order of dendrite

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal medulla oblongata morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: vacuoles began to appear in various nuclei in medulla at 2 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal medulla oblongata morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: edematous regions/lesions in the dorsal medulla (in the vestibular nucleus) extensive bilateral neuroinflammation in the vestibular nucleus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal medulla oblongata morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: edematous regions/lesions in the dorsal medulla (in the vestibular nucleus) extensive bilateral neuroinflammation in the vestibular nucleus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal medulla oblongata morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased number of apoptotic cells compared to controls at 12.5 dpc

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal proplatelet formation in cultured fetal liver-derived megakaryocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: megakaryocytes show a reduced polyploidization expression analysis shows inappropriate expression of mast cell and eosinophil specific genes in the megakaryocyte lineages

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: no mature megakaryocyte colonies or cells are obtained from yolk sacs or fetal livers and ES cells fail to differentiate into mature megakaryocytic cells in vitro, indicating an early block in megakaryocyte development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: no mature megakaryocyte colonies or cells are obtained from yolk sacs or fetal livers and ES cells fail to differentiate into mature megakaryocytic cells in vitro, indicating an early block in megakaryocyte development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased number of megakaryocytes defect in the formation of proplatelet-producing megakaryocytes no significant increase in the number of platelets in the peripheral blood

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: with neutrophil inclusions in the bone marrow

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: with neutrophil inclusions in the bone marrow

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the cytoplasmic to nuclear ratio is decreased compared to in wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: micro-megakaryocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte progenitor cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: no megakaryocyte colonies can be generated from yolk sac cells unlike when wild-type cells are cultured

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte progenitor cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bone marrow cultured in the presence of thrompoietin for only small colonies unlike similarly treated wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte progenitor cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a 5.4-fold increase in the number of colony-forming units present in an in vitro colony forming assay from spleen the colonies derived from bone marrow cells are much smaller and contain significantly fewer acetylcholinesterase positive cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal megakaryocyte progenitor cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: megakaryocyte-erythroid progenitors (MEPs) are significantly induced (>2.5 fold) in the spleen, but not in bone marrow

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal meiosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: most meiotic chromosomes in mutant mice display elongated chromosome axes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal meiotic spindle assembly checkpoint
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: persistent activation of the spindle assembly checkpoint

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal meiotic spindle assembly checkpoint
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: persistent activation of the spindle assembly checkpoint in oocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal meiotic spindle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal spindle orientation in granulosa cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal melanoblast migration
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in neural tube cultures, melanoblasts are unable to migrate out from the neural tube

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal melanoblast morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decrease in the number of melanoblasts between E12.5 and E13.5, with absence of melanoblasts in the trunk region at E13.5 increase in melanoblast apoptosis at E12.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal melanoblast morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5/P0, all mice exhibit an area of reduced melanoblasts in the tail compared with just over half of wild-type mice at P2, most mice exhibit an area of reduced melanoblasts in the tail compared with few wild-type mice at P8, over half of mice exhibit an area of reduced melanoblasts in the tail unlike in wild-type mice the boundaries of hypopigmentation are stable over time at P28, hypopigmented epidermis in the skin contains no lacZ-positive cells in the scales or hair with some scales at the edge being lightly pigmented and containing less dendritic melanocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal melanoblast morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show complete loss of LacZ+ melanoblasts in the bulge area at the end stage of hair follicle morphogenesis (i.e. stage 8, but not stage 6), indicating apoptosis of bulge melanocyte stem cells; in contrast, pigmented melanocytes are still maintained in the bulb at stage 8 mice treated with an anti-TGF-beta blocking antibody during the process of stem cell entry to the dormant state (stage 5-8) exhibit increased survival (rescue) of bulge LacZ+ melanoblasts at P4, P6, and P8, whereas untreated mice or mice treated with a control antibody display virtual loss of LacZ+ melanoblasts from the bulge area by P8

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal melanocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: degenerative changes are prevalent

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal melanocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: melanocyte cultures from the skin produce fewer than 10% initial melanocyte colonies that are non-proliferating unlike wild-type cultures

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal melanocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: melanocyte cultures from the skin produces fewer melanocytes than wild-type cultures and melanocytes exhibit aberrant morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal melanocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in P58 tail whole mounts, melanocytes (MCs) show a more stubby dendritic morphology with dendritic shortening and a more spread cell body area relative to MCs in control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal melanosome morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: clumps of melanosomes are visible in the few remaining pigmented hair follicles

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal meninges morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the meningeal cell layer does not extend into the developing cerebellar folia and between the cortical hemispheres remodeling of the meningeal basement membrane is defective starting at E15.5 and becomes progressively worse such that by P7, extracellular matrix molecules are absent from areas of the brain surface underlying the meninges

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mental foramen morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the mental foramen becomes very enlarged and forms a protruding bulge of tissue formed from the back end of the incisor

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mesangial cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5, mesangial cells fail to form a tree-like mesangial core and remain localized in a compact cluster at the center of the glomerular tuft mesangial cells fail to make the normal focal contacts with the GBM

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mesenchyme morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lack of branchial arch formation and head development implies a lack of mesenchymal expansion

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mesenchyme morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tamoxifen treatment at E6.5 results in collapse of the mesenchyme

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mesenchyme morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E10.5, mutant embryos display a highly disorganized and degenerated mesenchyme, with pyknotic bodies and debris detected throughout the tissue

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mesenteric lymph node morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: nodes are small, with medulla and occasionally entire lymph node replaced with connective tissue

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mesoderm development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: by E7.75, anterior mesodermal wings of mesoderm layer around embryo circumference are only one cell layer thick compared to 3-4 layers in wild-type embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mesoderm development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: differentiating at E7.5 but migrating poorly few intercellular spaces among invaginating mesoderm cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mesoderm development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: E7.5-8.5 mutants lack an obvious mesoderm layer

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mesoderm development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygotes display mesodermal and caudal dysgenesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mesoderm morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decrease in cephalic mesoderm at E10 in embryos treated with tamoxifen at E8.0

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metabolism
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit decreased metabolic rates compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metabolism
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced brain polyamine content

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metabolism
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: produce more CO2 and heat

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metabolism
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in induced endotoxic shock, metabolism of endogenously generated nitrosothiols is severely impaired

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metabolism
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following electrical stimulation, mutant EDL muscles exhibit increased nitric oxide (NO) metabolism (a 2.1-fold increase in cGMP formation) relative to wild-type EDL muscles in mutant EDS muscles, this increase is presumed to promote oxygen delivery by a NO-mediated vasodilation mechanism and is shown to be attenuated by a nitric oxide synthase inhibitor no significant increase in cGMP is observed between stimulated wild-type and mutant soleus muscles

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metanephric mesenchyme morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: failure to induce condensation of the metanephric mesenchyme

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metanephric mesenchyme morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: development of metanephric mesenchyme significantly retarded at E11.5 mesenchyme differentiation does not occur if ureteric bud fails to reach the metanephric mesenchyme

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metanephric mesenchyme morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E16.5, disruption of the cap mesenchyme is observed PAX2-expressing cap mesenchyme is longer detectable at E16.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metanephric mesenchyme morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after 3 days in organ culture, tubulogenesis within the metanephric blastema is significantly reduced

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metanephric ureteric bud development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E15.5, the ureteric bud undergoes premature epithelial differentiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metanephric ureteric bud development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in organ culture, lack of nephrogenic development is confirmed by staining for lectin D. biflorus which stains the ureteric bud

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metencephalon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: migration of facial branchiomotor neurons in the rhombencephalon is abnormal at E12.5 a dorsal migration of neurons is seen in r5 as well as in r6

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metopic suture morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: incomplete closure

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal metopic suture morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: heterotopic ossification in 1 pup at P0

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal microglial cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: activated microglia are detected in cerebellum at 1 month of age; macrophages are detected in Purkinje cell layer

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal microglial cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: activation of microglia starts at 1 year and by 2 years the white matter is crowded with epitheloid microglia activation of microglia tends to occur earlier and is more severe in the cerebellum than in the telencephalic hemispheres

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Purkinje cells have altered levels of particular tubulins and tubulin associated proteins at 18 days and 6 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal midbrain development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E10.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal midbrain-hindbrain boundary development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: more anterior position of dorsal boundary

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal midbrain-hindbrain boundary morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: slightly enlarged isthmic region at E17.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal middle ear epithelium morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: middle ear cavity epithelium of young mice is swollen by 16 months, cilia density is diminished and epithelial swelling is more pronounced

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal middle ear morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: although abnormalities are not found in the inner ear, all ears with elevated ABR thresholds have middle ear defects such as retracted tympanic membrane, effusion in the middle ear, thickened epithelium with fibrous polyps, and in older mice the excessive accumulation of discharge in the external ear canal

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal midface morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced midfacial width

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal milk composition
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in mutant mammary glands, expression of whey acidic protein (WAP), a late differentiation marker, is absent at P18 and reduced at L1

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal milk composition
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant females produce milk that is lethal to the offspring at 5-8 days of age; however, the fat and protein components appear to be normal and no differences in fatty acid or in vitamin A and D content are observed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal milk zinc level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant lactating dams produce lethal milk that contains 34% less zinc than that of wild-type dams

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal milk zinc level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: dams produce zinc-deficient milk that is lethal to all nursing pups

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mineral level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice from mothers on the acceleration diet during pregnancy exhibit extensive mineralization in the dermal sheath of vibrissae as early as 4 weeks of age and progresses with age, showing a 17.7-fold increase in mineral content of the muzzle skin containing vibrissae at 7 weeks of age, mice on the acceleration diet show severe mineralization in the muzzle area, showing calcium and phosphorus in a 2:1 ratio, similar to that in endochondral bone and the presence of hydroxyapatite mice from mothers on the acceleration diet during pregnancy exhibit extensive mineralization in the aorta, the coronary and carotid arteries, the retina, the blood vessels of the liver, and in the kidneys on a normal diet, mutants exhibit less mineralization in the dermal sheath of vibrissae on a normal diet, vascular mineralization is not seen until around 5 months of age compared to 4 weeks of age on the acceleration diet

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal miniature endplate potential
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in the proximal forelimb muscle  at P0, miniature endplate potentials are subthreshold and never result in action potentials unlike in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal miniature endplate potential
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lower frequency at E16 and E18

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal miniature excitatory postsynaptic currents
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show a slight increase in the amplitude of mEPSCs in somatosensory cortex layers 2-3 pyramidal neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal miniature excitatory postsynaptic currents
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the frequency of mEPSC, but not sEPSC, is depressed in females the frequency of mEPSC is depressed in males the mESPC decay time is prolonged in males but not females

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal miniature excitatory postsynaptic currents
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutants exhibit an increase in the frequency, but not amplitude, of miniature excitatory postsynaptic currents in layers 2/3 of acute medial prefrontal cortex slices

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal miniature inhibitory postsynaptic currents
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: current decay of mIPSCs is slower in females, but not males

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decreased oxidative capacity in the mitochondria of brown adipose tissue

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: functional inhibition of the NADH-dependent (Complex I) within the mitochondrial electron transport chain and activation of Complex II in embryonic motor neurons derived from mutant mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: absence of functional ETC components is likely responsible for the drastic reduction of ATP production

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: CI complex activity is decreased by half compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fibroblasts exhibit stalled assembly of complex 1 in the mitochondria compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondrial electron transfer capacity (ETC) is significantly reduced in cardiac homogenates reduction in OXPHOS results in a lower respiratory control ratio (RCR) indicating that mitochondria are less efficient at producing ATP; effects are apparent regardless of which substrate is used for electron donation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: significant decrease in complex I and complex II-dependent respiratory chain capacity in liver

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ATP concentration and ATP/ADP ratio are decreased in the kidney, slightly decreased in muscle, and slightly increased in the brain and liver at 4 months of age ATP levels and ATP/ADP ratio are decreased in the kidney and brain but are increased in the liver and muscle at 6 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: skin fibroblasts exhibit decreased complex 1 activity in the mitochondria compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: significantly reduced ATP production by mitochondria

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial crista morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fewer and shorter cristae displaced to the periphery with varying degrees of disorientation in the mitochondria of brown adipose tissue

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial crista morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondria exhibit far fewer cristae at E7.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial crista morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: nerves in areas of neuronal degeneration exhibit mitochondria with compact and/or swollen cristae unlike in wild-type mice
