OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial crista morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal mitochondria with tubular and branching cristae are seen after 56 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial crista morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: neuromelanin organelle-containing SNpc dopaminergic neurons show mitochondria with disrupted cristae

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial crista morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a few mitochondria in the striatum of 15 month old mice have altered crista morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial crista morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: by 23 months of age, mitochondria exhibit crista swelling, disorganization and severely condensed mitochondria mitochondria with disorganized cristae is seen in the hippocampus and cortex, with the cortex more affected than the hippocampus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial crista morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the mitochondria observed in mutant diaphragm or tibialis anterior (TA) contained extensive and compact cristae

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial crista morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormally swollen or absent cristae

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial fission
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondrial defects consistent with mitochondrial fission arrest

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E7.5, TEM shows a marked alteration in mitochondrial morphology, with many large vesicle-like structures present within every mitochondrion

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: already at 15 weeks of age, mutants exhibit presence of abnormal mitochondria with degenerated inner membranes and mitochondria collapse in axons increase of cardiolipin suggests insufficient remodeling of mitochondrial inner membranes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit mitochondrial degeneration in SNpc dopaminergic neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bone marrow cell mitochondria of pI-pC treated mice show prominent contours of the membranes and are swollen accumulation of iron in mitochondria of bone marrow cells of pI-pC treated mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: EM analysis of L5 neocortical pyramidal neurons revealed an increase in mitochondrial density and a more rounded shape, consistent with increased mitochondrial fission

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: although individual mitochondria are formed with a normal number of cristae, inter-myofibrillar mitochondria are markedly disorganized in cardiac tissue numerous spherical electron dense inclusion bodies are observed within the mitochondria of cardiac cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondria in the striatum of 15 month old mice have altered distribution, clustering in the neuropils, and a few have altered shape and crista morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondria in the striatum of 23 month old mutants are about 10% longer

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the complete absence of mitochondrial matrix granules in the mutant tissue samples of kidney and to lesser extent in liver

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in cells of the cerebellum

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increase in intracellular calcium concentration and presence of hyperfused mitochondria in MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondria of myoepithelial cells are swollen and lack normal crystal structures mitochondria in some mutant muscle fibers are swollen and exhibit degeneration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondrial produce more hydrogen peroxide compared to in wild-type cells male mice exhibit a faster rate of mitochondrial dysfunction compared with female mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased basal mitochondrial membrane potential in embryonic motor neurons derived from mutant mice, as shown by a 27% increase in tetramethylrhodamine methylester (TMRM) signal relative to wild-type motor neurons significant reduction of mitochondrial membrane potential in embryonic motor neurons (~17% fall in TMRM signal) following exposure to oligomycin (an inhibitor of the F1FO-ATP synthase), unlike in wild-type motor neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: some reduced state 3 respiration in mitochondria from 6-months old mice and state 2 and state 3 respiration in mitochondria from 12-months old mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: embryos show a significantly higher ADP to ATP ratio, indicating mitochondrial dysfunction

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: activity of mitochondrial complex I or III is reduced in the substantia nigra mice show a reduced level of intracellular ATP production in the substantia nigra mice exhibit an overproduction of ROS, increased level of lipid peroxidation of mitochondria, and upregulated cytosolic level of cytochrome c in the substantia nigra, indicating further mitochondrial dysfunction level of cytosolic cytochrome c, active caspase-9 and active caspase 3 are increased in the substantia nigra at 9 months of age, indicating activation of mitochondrial apoptotic pathway

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decreased mitochondrial respiration after ischemia and reperfusion

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: isolated neocortical mitochondria exhibit reduced ATP production in a luciferase-based ATP synthesis assay

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impaired calcium intake in heart mitochondria reduced calcium intramitochondrial in skeletal muscle stimulated with caffeine through permeability transition pores

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: slight decrease in mitochondrial calcium in skeletal muscle fiber

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: severe decrease of in organello translation in the hearts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced translation of proteins larger than 25 kDa in hepatocytes slightly increased translation of proteins smaller than 25 kDa in hepatocytes impaired formation and/or activity of respiratory complexes I, III and IV in hepatocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: hyperpolarization of mitochondrial membranes in MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tamoxifen-treated mice exhibit compromised mitochondrial respiration due to defects in protein lipoylation and respiratory complexes compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased mitochondrial biogenesis in muscle

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial shape
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: L5 neocortical pyramidal neurons exhibit a more rounded mitochondrial shape (decreased aspect ratio)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial shape
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a few mitochondria in the striatum of 15 month old mice have altered shape

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial shape
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondria in the striatum of 15 month old mice have abnormal shape that resembles beads-on-the-string

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial shape
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: immunofluorescence analysis of primary diaphragm myoblasts revealed mitochondria that are significantly more elongated in mutant mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial shape
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondria from gastrocnemius muscles of 1 month old mice are enlarged and irregularily shaped

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitochondrial shape
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondria from gastrocnemius muscles of 1 month old mice are enlarged and irregularily shaped

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: autophagy/mitophagy-related protein levels are decreased in the substantia nigra, indicating impaired mitophagy

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitophagy
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased autophagy of mitochondria

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in MEFs tamoxifen treatment results in an accumulation of cells in G1/G0 and loss of S-phase and mitotic cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: E3.5 embryos grown in culture exhibit aberrant mitosis, such as displaced chromosomes from the metaphase plate

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fibroblasts infected with adenovirus encoding cre show mitotic abnormalities with defects in chromosome alignments; in some cases, one or two chromosomes are displaced from the metaphase plate, in other cases chromosomes fail to align or are clustered near the poles in a centrophilic position percentage of mitotic cells with misaligned chromosomes increases over time, from 28% at 24 hours postinfection with adenovirus encoding cre to 43% at 48 hours postinfection misaligned chromosomes result from a failure of chromosomes to congress, not from premature sister chromatid separation fibroblasts grown in vitro show a reduced number of kinetochore-associated microtubules

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following liver injury, hepatocytes from mutants treated with an adenoviral cre, exhibit abnormal mitosis with misaligned, centrophilic chromosomes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 14% of mitotic figures from splenocytes show premature separation of sister chromatids in MEFs chromosome segregation defects resulting from chromosome lagging or congression failure are observed at much higher rates than in wild-type MEFs; most events involve a single chromosome but some involve two or three chromosomes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 15% of mitotic figures from splenocytes show premature separation of sister chromatids in MEFs chromosome segregation defects resulting from chromosome lagging or congression failure are observed at much higher rates than in wild-type MEFs; most events involve a single chromosome but some involve two or three chromosomes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in MEFs chromosome segregation defects resulting from chromosome lagging or congression failure are observed at much higher rates than in wild-type MEFs; most events involve a single chromosome but some involve two or three chromosomes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in MEFs chromosome segregation defects resulting from chromosome lagging or congression failure are observed at much higher rates than in wild-type MEFs; most events involve a single chromosome but some involve two or three chromosomes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: neural stem cells show unusually large, Hoechst-dense structures at prophase, however the kinetics of mitotic progression is normal chromosome segregation defects at anaphase and postmitotic cells at E16.5 defects in mitotic chromosome architecture and segregation are more prominent than in mice conditionally deleted for Ncaph the numbers of chromocenters (the nuclear structure that forms from the association of pericentric heterochromatin from several different chromosomes during interphase) per nucleus in the ventricular zone are greatly decreased; this is due to hyperclustering of chromocenters and not due to loss of chromocenters hyperclustering of chromocenters occurs in neural stem cells and in postmitotic neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: an increase in the frequency of chromatin bridge formation during anaphase is seen in apical neural progenitors during neurogenesis at E13.5 indicating that chromosome segregation is impaired mouse embryonic fibroblasts exhibit higher levels of chromosome segregation defects mice exhibit an increase in frequency of micronucleated reticulocytes and mature erythrocytes due to segregation errors

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 17% of anaphases have multiple lagging chromosomes compared to 0% in wild-type MEFs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: incidence of premature chromosome separation in mouse embryonic fibroblasts is increased compared to in wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: premature sister chromatid separation in mouse embryonic fibroblasts shortened mitotic timing

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: MEFs and mitotic splenocytes exhibit premature chromatid separation MEFs exhibit small, but significant, increase in chromosome segregation errors; both spindle assembly checkpoint and attachment error correction machinery are impaired MEFs exhibit increased chromosome lagging, forming non-perpendicular spindles and elevated rates due to slow centrosome movement

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: MEFs and mitotic splenocytes exhibit premature chromatid separation MEFs exhibit small, but significant, increase in chromosome segregation errors; both spindle assembly checkpoint and attachment error correction machinery are impaired MEFs exhibit increased chromosome lagging, forming non-perpendicular spindles and elevated rates due to slow centrosome movement

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: MEFs exhibit impaired centrosome movement and form non-perpendicular spindles at increased rates MEFs show an increase in chromatin bridges premature chromatid separation in mitotic splenocytes from 5-month old mice is elevated

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: MEFs exhibit impaired centrosome movement and form non-perpendicular spindles at increased rates premature chromatid separation in mitotic splenocytes from 5-month old mice is elevated

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: MEFs exhibit premature chromatid separation MEFs exhibit small, but significant, increase in chromosome segregation errors; both spindle assembly checkpoint and attachment error correction machinery are impaired

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: MEFs show premature chromatid separation MEFs exhibit higher rates of chromosome missegregation and more severely compromised error correction MEFs exhibit impaired centrosome movement and form non-perpendicular spindles at increased rates

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mouse embryonic fibroblasts infected with a cre-expressing adenovirus exhibit delay in G1 to S and G2/M to G1 progression compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impaired in seminiferous tubules with unaligned chromosomes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant MEFs show a 7-fold increase in the ratio of preanaphase mitotic cells with unaligned chromosomes; chromosomes are not aligned in live MEFs prior to anaphase mutant germ cells in the E12.5 fetal gonad exhibit similar chromosome alignment defects and undergo mitotic arrest

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitosis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitotic cells are mostly in prometaphase (72%) chromosomes remain dispersed in cytoplasm

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitotic cytokinesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mis-segregated chromosomes with DNA bridges located at the cleavage furrow

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the spindle assembly checkpoint is defective in tamoxifen-treated mouse embryonic fibroblasts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: taxol-treated mouse embryonic fibroblasts exhibit severe defects in spindle assembly checkpoints compared to in similarly treated wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuromuscular synapse morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: severe morphological defects in neuromuscular junctions (NMJs) formed at the extensor hallucis longus (EHL) muscle at 8-10 weeks of age large dystrophic swellings in presynaptic terminals as well as in synapses onto the tibialis anterior and diaphragm muscles, suggesting a generalized defect in NMJ architecture frequency of swellings is significantly increased at 2-3 and 6.5 months of age, suggesting a progressive neurodegenerative disease

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuromuscular synapse morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P0 nerve terminals in the forelimbs are well-developed but sprouted suggesting a history of inactivity

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuromuscular synapse morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: endplates are scattered in the diaphragm compared with wild-type mice muscle fibers exhibit multiple endplates in the diaphragm unlike in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuromuscular synapse morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: neuromuscular junctions in the abdominal, soleus, and gastrocnemius muscles and the diaphragm appear immature in mutants at P21

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuromuscular synapse morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit a delay in eliminating nerve endings after axotomy compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron differentiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron differentiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron differentiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in vivo, CA1 hipoocampal and cortical neurons in 10-week old mice show a reduction in dendritic spine density (103 spines/100 um or 91 spines/100 um in wild-type hippocampal or cortical neurons (layer 1) compared to 88 spines/100 um or 68.4 spines/100 um in mutant hippocampal or cortical neurons)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following transfection with GFP-cre at DIV9, neurons exhibit a reduction in dendritic filopodia compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: intraneuronal accumulation of autofluoerscent material in the cortex, cerebellum, and other CNS regions including the hippocampus, vestibular nuclei, inferior olivary nucleus, and spinal cord at 16 months of age cells accumulating autofluorescence co-label with beta-galactosidase, Ctip2, SatB2, parvalbumin or calbindin, suggesting that principal cells as well as inhibitory interneurons are affected large clusters of irregularly shaped electron-dense lipofuscin-like deposits and membranous structures filled with autophagic material are found in cortical, hippocampal pyramidal neurons, and spinal cord neurons at 16 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5, acetylcholine receptor density in the diaphragm is reduced 40% compared to in wild-type neurons at E18.5, neuronal processes in the diaphragm grow beyond the synaptic band region unlike in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 1 year of age, neurons exibiting abnormal sulfatide storage with no obvious cellular damage include several nuclei of the brainstem, diencephalon, spinal chord, and cerebellum

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: neurons in the striatum have less spines on distal dendrites at 24 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: striatal neurons are smaller than in wild-type mice with smaller cell bodies

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cultured E18 hippocampal neurons show 60.1% less neurite outgrowth (sum of axonal and dendrite length) than wild-type neurons after 5 days leading edge of growth cone rarely extended to tips of filopodia lamellipodia extend at rate of 6.85 um/minute compared to 5.84 um/minute observed in wild-type cultured neurons, but retraction velocity is similar for both genotypes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: perforated patch recordings on neocortical pyramidal neurons revealed that the resting membrane potential is significantly more negative than that in wild-type neurons, consistent with lower intracellular ATP levels following treatment with tolbutamide (a K<sup>+</sup><sub>ATP</sub> channel inhibitor), pyramidal neurons fail to exhibit a more positive membrane potential, unlike in wild-type neurons following treatment with sodium azide (NaN<sub>3</sub>), a complex IV inhibitor that indirectly decreases ATP, pyramidal neurons fail to exhibit a significant decrease in membrane potential, unlike in wild-type neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Purkinje cells show a moderate decrease in firing frequency

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal neuron physiology

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P10, Tbr2+ intermediate neuronal progenitors fail to translocate to the subgranular zone and the hilum of the dentate gyrus, with some of Tbr2+ progenitors remaining at the outer rim of the molecular cell layer only a few NeuroD1+ neuroblasts are present in the granular cell of the dentate gyrus at P10, and almost none is found in the subgranular zone at P24, indicating abnormal migration of NeuroD1+ neuroblasts cell cycle progression of the dentate migration stream is impaired at E15.5, most likely through the G1 phase

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oculomotor nerve morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oculomotor nerve morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oculomotor nerve morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: oculomotor (III) appears deformed at E10.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal olfactory sensory neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: olfactory axons exhibit abnormal projections in the dorsocaudal olfactory bulb and, unlike in wild-type mice most axons do not terminate in discrete glomeruli

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oligodendrocyte differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show a transient delay in oligodendrocytes (OL) maturation and myelination: cells expressing Myrf protein (an OL maturity marker) in transverse spinal cord sections are reduced to 56% of controls at P7, with similar decreases noted in cells expressing myelin genes Mbp and Plp1 and Gstpi protein; at P30 only a slight reduction in Gstpi numbers is still observed, whereas no differences in all other differentiation markers and myelin genes are detected at P30 or P60

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oligodendrocyte differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decrease in the number of Plp1+ mature oligodendrocytes from P0 to P15 treatment with a T3 analog (GC-1) but not with T4, stimulates oligodendrocyte differentiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: oocytes were observed to be enlarged and misshapen, first evident at 8 days of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P3 some primordial follicles show an increase in the size of primary oocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: nearly all oocytes arrest at the germinal vesicle (GV) stage without undergoing nuclear envelope breakdown or completing meiosis many poly(A) mRNAs are transformed into uridylated-poly(A) mRNAs which are more stable, resulting in global accumulation of transcripts uridylated-poly(A) RNAs are stabilized due to insufficient degradation and tail editing insufficient degradation of meiotic repressor transcripts may cause GV arrest

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: some superovulated oocytes have an abnormal morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: MPF is not activated in oocytes and they do not undergo germinal vesicle breakdown folliculogenesis and ovulation were unimpaired

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: apparent asynchronous development of the oocyte and follicle

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the number of eggs obtained from mutant females is about 50% that from control females lacking Tg(Zp3-cre)1Gwh and more mutant females failed to produce any eggs after superovulation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the number of eggs obtained from mutant females is about 50% that from control females lacking Tg(Zp3-cre)1Gwh and more mutant females failed to produce any eggs after superovulation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal operant conditioning behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impaired behavior in a sucrose pellets self-administration paradigm

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal operant conditioning behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in an operant-responding task to acquire a high fat diet pellet, individually-housed females exhibit fewer nose pokes and earn fewer rewards than wild-type mice, indicating reduced preference for high-fat diet

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal operant conditioning behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in the operant responding test to acquire a high fat diet pellet, males, but not females, tend to be less motivated to press the lever to obtain high-fat pellets after overnight fasting

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ophthalmic nerve morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced and fails to extend over the lens at E10.5 in some embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic chiasm morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: optic chiasm tends to form more caudal to anterior commissure

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic choroid morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at birth the choroid fissure is irregularly closed in the anterior eye and open from the posterior part of the lens to the rear of the optic cup in newborns the retinal eversion remains obvious in the unclosed portions of the choroid fissure

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic choroid morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: remains open at E12 and in areas along the edges inversion of the pigment epithelium is seen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic cup morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: arching of the cup is reduced and the medial-lateral diameter is increased at E10.5 abnormal morphology persists through E11.5 at P0 the cup is poorly arched around the lens

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic cup morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: slightly reduced in size from E13 onwards irregularly formed surrounding less than half of the spherical lens

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic cup morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 27 days optic cup is observed to be larger than control

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic cup morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: disoriented in 74 of 122 embryos at E10.5-E12.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic fissure closure
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E12 the choroid fissure is mostly closed but the joining of the retinal nervous layer is not smooth and a large retinal eversion is present at the rear of the optic cup where the fissure fails to close in newborns the retinal eversion remains obvious in the unclosed portions of the choroid fissure

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic nerve innervation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: retinal axon projections form an H shaped optic chiasm at E15 retinal axons project correctly toward the dorsal thalamus, but fail to terminate

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic nerve morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: show decreased cross-sectional area of optic nerve, reflecting a 29% loss of retinal ganglion cell axons, at P15 but not at P10, the time after the period of naturally occurring cell death

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic nerve morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the optic nerve is hypomyelinated and axonal diameters are reduced compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic nerve morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: there is a 15% reduction in cross-sectional area of the optic nerve compared to wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic stalk morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased diameter of the stalk at E10.5 abnormal morphology persists through E11.5 optic stalk is still present at E14, E16, and P0 when in control littermates it is nearly or completely absent

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic stalk morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: slight increase in diameter at E11 shorter and somewhat greater in diameter at E11.5 and E12

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal optic stalk morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at P13 (but not at P1, homozygotes display degeneration of the optic stalk

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal orbit morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 3 of 36 heterozygotes exhibit only a vestigial dysplastic ocular remnant unilaterally, associated with a malformation of the orbit

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal organ of Corti morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the organ of Corti is decreased in length compared to in wild-type mice at E17.5, the organ of Corti is disorganized unlike in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal organ of Corti morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the structural integrity of the organ of Corti is altered with supporting and hair cells not exhibiting their normal vertical height and a slight compression of the organ, especially at the apical half turn

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal organ of Corti supporting cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5 and 3-5 months, heterozygotes display distortion of the upper surfaces of supporting cells that are immediately adjacent to misoriented OHCs

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal organ of Corti supporting cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: supporting not exhibiting their normal vertical height

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal orientation of cochlear hair cell stereociliary bundles
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: irregular

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal orientation of outer hair cell stereociliary bundles
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: adult heterozygotes display mildly misoriented OHC stereociliary bundles in the apical cochlear relative to Celsr1<sup>Scy</sup> heterozygotes, with fewer OHCs being affected in contrast, IHC stereociliary bundle orientation remains unaffected

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal orientation of outer hair cell stereociliary bundles
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5 and 3-5 months, heterozygotes display excessive misoriented OHC stereociliary bundles, esp. in the apical cochlear turn relative to wild-type mice (apex 3.60%, base 1.68% rotated vs apex 0.66%, base 0.18% rotated, respectively) in the apex, OHC bundle misorientation is noted as early as E16.5 in contrast, IHC stereociliary bundles remain unaffected

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal orientation of outer hair cell stereociliary bundles
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5, homozygotes display extensive rotation of OHC stereociliary bundles along the entire length of the cochlear duct orientation of OHC bundles is random, including some bundles with a rotation of ~180Â° relative to the normal plane of orientation in the apex, OHC bundle misorientation is noted as early as E16.5 in contrast, IHC stereociliary bundle orientation remains unaffected

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal orientation of outer hair cell stereociliary bundles
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E18.5, homozygotes display extensive rotation of OHC stereociliary bundles along the entire length of the cochlear duct orientation of OHC bundles is random, including some bundles with a rotation of ~180Â° relative to the normal plane of orientation in the apex, OHC bundle misorientation is noted as early as E16.5 in contrast, IHC stereociliary bundle orientation remains unaffected

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal orientation of outer hair cell stereociliary bundles
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: some outer hair cell stereociliary hair bundles are misoriented or have a flattened shape

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoblast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: delay in differentiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoblast morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: extensive vacuolization is seen in cultures of isolated osteoblasts from calvarial tissue

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoblast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: high osteoblast activity at 21 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoblast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: osteoblasts have decreased levels of alkaline phosphatase activity calvariae osteoblasts cultured in vitro are unable to form bony nodules as wild-type controls are

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoblast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: osteoblasts reduce their proliferation and their alkaline phosphatase activity by a greater amount than controls when cultured with IL-6 family cytokines proliferation reduction caused by IL-6/sIL-6R, IL-11, and LIF were 43%, 36%, and 13% compared to 32%, 20%, and 10% in controls osteoblast activity is increased 2.8- and 2.0- fold compared to controls when cultured with IL-6/sIL-6R or IL-11

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoblast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: there is no suppressive effect of IL-6 family cytokines on the proliferation of osteoblasts isolated from E18.5 calvariae the induction of ALP activity by the IL-6 family cytokines IL-6, IL-11, and OSM is markedly suppressed in these mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoblast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: osteoblasts exhibit hypercalcification compared with wild-type cell

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: while basal osteoclastogenesis was normal, osteoclastogenesis was impaired relative to controls in response to an osteoclastogenic stimulus (the calcitropic hormone PTHrP) bone marrow-derived macrophages do not exhibit a robust osteoclastogenic response to M-CSF and RANK-L as seen in wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: unfractionated bone marrow cells produce more osteoclasts in vitro when cultured with various differentiation factors maximal numbers of osteoclasts form from bone marrow cultures after 6 days in the presence of RANKL, while maximal numbers are not reached until 9 days in wild-type cultures highly purified osteoclast precursors form increased numbers of osteoclasts in response to TNF and RANKL compared to wild-type highest number of osteoclasts develop when mutant precursors are cultured with mutant bone marrow stromal cells mutant bone marrow stromal cells double the differentiation rate in vitro of wild-type osteoclast precursors into osteoclasts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: osteoclast formation from bone marrow macrophages is increased compared to from wild-type bone marrow

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: osteoclast formation from bone marrow macrophages is increased compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bone marrow-derived monocytes grown in culture exhibit fast and premature in vitro osteoclastogenesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: fewer osteoclasts differentiate from cultured mutant bone marrow cells stimulated with an osteotropic factor than from stimulated wild-type bone marrow cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: enhanced osteoclastogenesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: osteoclasts are larger and more ovoid in shape when compared to wild-type controls the ruffled borders of mutant osteoclasts are thicker, blunter, and fewer in number the number of folds in the ruffled border is reduced by 6-fold or more

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in vitro and in vivo osteoclast differentiation is disrupted compared with wild-type controls impaired osteoclast differentiation cannot be corrected by TNF-alpha treatment

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: small osteoclasts

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cells are smaller, rounder, and contain fewer nuclei than in heterozygous controls the ratio of regular to irregular nuclei is significantly greater in homozygotes compared to heterozygous controls cells contain greater amounts of cytoplasmic basophilia and cytoplasmic RNA compared to heterozygous controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased size at P1 but not at P37 and 3 to 8 months

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 3 of 20 osteoclasts from bone lesions exhibit nuclear inclusions unlike wild-type cells osteoclasts that differentiate from bone marrow macrophage are larger and contained more nuclei than osteoclasts that differentiate from wild-type macrophage

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant mice have reduced osteoclast cell surface

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: TRAP activity is decreased at P37 but not at 3 to 8 months

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: a 1.5-fold increase in bone resorption is observed when osteoclasts are treated with RANKL (50 ng/ml) and cultured on dentin however, the area resorbed per osteoclasts is not different between mutant and wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: high osteoclast activity at 21 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: eroded bone surface which is an indicator of osteoclast function is 199% greater than in wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: bone marrow-derived mononuclear cells cultured with M-CSF and RANKL exhibit decreased surface area covered by osteoclasts and resorptive activity compared with similarly treated wild-type cultures

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteoclast physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: osteoblasts have decreased levels of alkaline phosphatase activity calvariae osteoblasts cultured in vitro are unable to form bony nodules as wild-type controls are

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal osteocyte morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased number of poorly aligned osteocytes with plump (immature) morphology in the maxilla, calvaria and mandible at P0 reduction in Sost (sclerostin)-positive cells in the maxillary bone at P0, suggesting delayed osteocyte maturation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal otic vesicle development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ossification of the otic vesicle is impaired

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal otic vesicle development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased apoptosis at E10.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal otolith morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show variable losses of saccular otoconia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal otolith morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: absence of utricular otoconia saccular, but not utricular, otolith defect is alleviated by zinc supplementation of the dam gigantic crystals are seen in the saccule

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal otolith morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the ololith is abnormally shaped unlike in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal outer dense fiber morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mature spermatids exhibit an anomaly at the level of outer dense fiber (ODF) extension in the fibrous sheath an ODF of abnormal length is seen along doublet 8 or doublet 3, unlike in wild-type cells where shorter ODFs are typically associated with the axonemal doublets 3 and 8 and are not seen in transverse section when the longitudinal columns (LCs) are present

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal outer dense fiber morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: elongating spermatids show displacement of the outer dense fibers (ODFs)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal outer dense fiber morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: almost all epididymal sperm have misplaced or missing outer dense fibers (ODFs)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal outer dense fiber morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: displaced in the mid-piece of sperm flagella

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal outer ear cartilage morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ectopic ossification at age 18 weeks

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal outer hair cell kinocilium location or orientation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in the apex at E16.5, the kinocilium is found in abnormal positions

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal outer hair cell kinocilium location or orientation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in the apex at E16.5, the kinocilium is found in abnormal positions

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal outer hair cell stereociliary bundle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: as early as P1, mice exhibit defects in stereocilia bundles with peripheral stereocilia deviating outward compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovarian follicle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in some ovaries a disproportionate increase in oocyte size relative to the follicular cells is seen at P30

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovarian follicle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ovaries show only interstitial cells and no follicle structures

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovarian follicle number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increase in the number of follicles at P30

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovarian follicle number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: decrease in the total number of follicles at 6 and 12 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovarian follicle number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: sterile female adults have a dramatic reduction in the number of growing follicles while the phenotype is less severe in fertile adult females and on this segregating background the phenotype varies considerably between individuals

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovarian follicle number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced number of developing follicles

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovarian folliculogenesis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased activation resulting in the progression of increased numbers of follicles to more advanced stages of follicular development increased atresia by 8.5 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovary morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: gonads irregularly shaped but of normal size at E12.5 gonad histology appeared normal but lacked a distinct mesenchymal zone

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovary morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 20 to 22 weeks of age some homozygotes have normal appearing ovaries while others have tiny ovaries with few to no follicles and subfertile homozygotes have premature ovarian failure

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovary morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ovaries were histologically normal through 21 days of age defects became apparent after 3 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovary physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after PMSG treatment with or without addition of hCG, LHR mRNA expression is lower than that in wild-type ovaries decreased LHR expression results in reduced serum estradiol and progesterone via reduced expression of key enzymes involved in steroidogenesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovary physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: ovaries explanted at birth and cultured for 8 days grow more rapidly than controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovary physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: apparent asynchronous development of the oocyte and follicle

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovary topology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: variable location of the ovaries

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal ovulation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: age of first ovulation is delayed relative to that in wild-type females (51.2 +/- 5.8 days versus 37.6 +/- 1.81 days)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oxidative phosphorylation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation (OXPHOS) is significantly reduced in cardiac homogenates

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oxidative phosphorylation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: when mitochondrial respiration is normalized to citrate synthase activity, male heterozygotes show a deficiency in OXPHOS and ETS (maximal respiration rate) relative to wild-type controls, whereas female mice do not

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal oxygen level
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygotes exhibit activation of compensatory mechanisms all of which tend to steepen the oxygen gradient from the capillary to the mitochondria and thereby augment the flux of oxygen

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal paired-pulse inhibition
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced after short bursts of five action potentials at 50 Hz and during 10-Hz action potential trains in cultured autaptic hippocampal glutamatergic neurons reduced after train stimulations with 25 pulses at 14 Hz in acute hippocampal slices

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatal mesenchymal cell proliferation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced proliferation of the posterior palatal mesenchyme but not of the anterior mesenchyme

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatal mesenchymal cell proliferation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mesenchymal cell proliferation is significantly reduced in E12.5 palatal shelves, resulting in lower cell density and smaller palatal shelves with limited ability to grow and fuse by E14.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatal mesenchymal cell proliferation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 40% decrease in mesenchymal proliferation in the oral domain of palatal shelves at E13.5, with disorganized mesenchymal cells lining the shelf epithelium

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatal mesenchymal cell proliferation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Ki67 immunohistochemistry showed a significant decrease in mesenchymal cell proliferation in middle palatal shelves sections at E12.5, with a more pronounced reduction observed at E15.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatal mesenchymal cell proliferation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Ki67 immunohistochemistry showed a significant decrease in mesenchymal cell proliferation in middle palatal shelves sections at E15.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatal rugae morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: disorganized in mice with submucous cleft

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatal shelf elevation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in some mice the anterior palatal shelves are deformed and fail to elevate

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatal shelf morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 15% increase in cell density in the nasal domain of palatal shelves at E13.5, with no differences observed in the oral domain

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palate bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: incomplete fusion of palatal bones is seen in skulls of newborn mutants

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: palatal shelves are reduced in size in the posterior region where the soft palate forms

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the palatal dimensions are proportionally smaller, however the structural components are in tact mutants exhibit reduced proliferation in the palate shelves at E14.5 and in the adjacent palatal epithelium mutants exhibit reduced hyaluronic acid in the palate shelves at E14.5 mutants exhibit aberrant vascular pattering in the palate including reduced vascular branching at E14.5 and E15.5

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: lacks development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatine bone horizontal plate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the palatal process is present but deformed and shifted laterally

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatine bone horizontal plate morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: palatine shelves retain a vertical position and fail to fuse along the midline

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatine bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the palatine bones are dysmorphic and do not extend towards the midline some small ectopic ossifications are found in the midline which may or may not be fragments of the palatine bones

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatine bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced in width

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatine bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced in width

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal palatine bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduction in palatine bone ossification

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreas development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: embryos show an increase in Neurog3+ve cells at E9.5; by E10.5, an increase in glucagon+ve cells is seen at E15.5, the insulin +ve area of the pancreatic tissue is reduced by 65% compared to control embryos proximal-distal patterning is altered in the embryonic pancreas; at E15.5, Nkx6-1+ve, Ptf1a-ve cells are reduced in the proximal domain by 75% while Hnf1b and DBA+ve cells are reduced in number at E12.5, Nkx6-1+ve Ptf1a-ve are present, but reduced in numbers by 50% compared to controls along with a corresponding increase in Nkx6-1-ve Ptf1a+ve cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreas morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 540 days, one mouse exhibit pancreatic preinvasive ductal lesions unlike wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreas morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: adult pancreas contains numerous adipoctyes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreas morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice develop peri-islet T cell aggregates >30 weeks of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreas morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increased vascularity

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreas physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: exhibit increased susceptibility to pancreatic injury (induced by cerulein to block secretion and induce acinar cell stress and experimental pancreatitis)

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreas physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Ryanodine-induced apoptosis and palmitate-induced apoptosis were prevented in isolated mutant  islet cells in vitro

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic acinar cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: acinar cell size is greatly reduced

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic acinar cell zymogen granule morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: acinar cells appear smaller with less zymogen granule content

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic acinus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: number of acini is greatly reduced pancreatic acini are dispersed and are not in close proximity to neighboring acini resulting in an expanded extracellular space the centroacinar duct is greatly expanded in adults

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic beta cell differentiation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E15.5, the insulin +ve area of the pancreatic tissue is reduced by 65% compared to control embryos

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic beta cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 3% of beta cells in 3 month old males are large with macronuclei, multiple nuclei and absent intranuclear septa

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic beta cell morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic beta cell physiology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic islet morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic islet morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic islet size
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduction in islet diameter at 1 month of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pancreatic islet size
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: slight reduction in islet diameter at 1 month of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal paranodal axoglial junction morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal pulmonary ventilation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal respiratory electron transport chain

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to infection

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to infection

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to novel object

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to novel object

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to novel object

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to novel object

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to novel object

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to novel object
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: while mice behave normally towards a novel object at 7 weeks post-infection with scrapie strain Rocky Mountain Laboratories, at 8 weeks post-infection mice exhibit an inability to recognize a novel object with no preference towards it that lasts through out the course of infection by week 12, novel object preference is reversed possibly due to preference for familiar objects and neophobia

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to novelty

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to radiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to radiation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to social novelty

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response to social novelty

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal response/metabolism to endogenous compounds

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal retina layer morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal retina layer morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal retina morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal retina morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal retina morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal retina pigment epithelium morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal retina pigment epithelium morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal retina vasculature morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sleep duration

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sleep pattern
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at the midday 3-hour period, mice wake more than wild-type mice at midday, mice exhibit less REM sleep than wild-type mice during the 12-hour recovery after 6 hours of prolonged waking, mice exhibit less waking and more short wave sleep compared to similarly treated wild-type mice mice are awake more during the mid-third of the light period compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sleep pattern
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice spend about 10-fold less time in REM sleep than controls during both light and dark phases mice also spend less time in non-REM sleep during the dark phase too

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sleep pattern
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at early as 5 months of age, mice exhibit higher scores of awaken (activity that ends rest periods) and twitch (activity that disrupts rest periods) compared with wild-type mice by 16 months, mice exhibit periods of lying on the floor inactive during the night phase indicating exhaustion

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal small intestinal crypt cell proliferation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal small intestine morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal small intestine morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal small intestine morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal social investigation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in the three chamber sociability test, P55-P65 mice fail to show preference for an unfamiliar caged wild-type mouse over a caged object, unlike controls in the juvenile social interaction test, P25-P35 mice tend to stay farther apart from their cage mate and show fewer nose-to-nose contacts than controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal social investigation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in the 3-chamber sociability test, mice show reduced sociability, with mice spending only slightly more time interacting with the stranger mouse than with the inanimate object

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal social investigation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: male and female mice exhibit reduced anogenital exploration compared with wild-type mice female mice exhibit increased social evasion compared with wild-type mice female mice exhibit reduced nonanogenital exploration and approach and follow behavior compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal social investigation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: males do not show a preference for a nonspecific stranger versus a new, inanimate object males exhibit diminished reciprocal interactions with a freely moving stranger mouse treatment with 4DGI-1, an inhibitor of Eif4e-Eif4g interactions, results in a decrease in repetitive behaviors, perseverative behaviors, and in social behavior deficits

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal social investigation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal social/conspecific interaction behavior
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: low social dominance

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal soleus morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal soleus morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal soleus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: soleus muscle appears pale at 8 weeks of age and pathological changes are seen at 6 months

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal soleus morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal soleus morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal somatic hypermutation frequency
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the percentage of mutations that occur in the recombined IgH locus of germinal center B cells is roughly half that of controls the mutation percentage drops to less than a third of controls when germinal center B cells are pre-screened to keep only those that have excised the floxed allele almost 50% of all sequences derived from these cells contained only one mutation, whereas close to 80% of the sequences derived from controls had multiple mutations

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal somatic hypermutation frequency
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: following immunization with NP-CGG in alum, splenic B cells exhibit reduced mutation frequency compared with wild-type cells Peyer's patch B cells exhibit increased accumulation of mutation at the intron downstream of rearranged V genes with altered patterns compared with wild-type cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal somatic hypermutation frequency
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: 10 fold reduction of transitions and transversions of template A/T compensatory increase of mutations on template G/C

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal somatic hypermutation frequency
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: splenic B cells had a higher rate of somatic mutations in the rearranged V186.2 gene segment after immunization with NP antigen the overall frequency of unique mutations at the V186.2 gene segment was 9.1 x 10<sup>-2</sup>  mutations/base, which was significantly higher than the 7.2 x 10<sup>-2</sup>  mutations/base detected in wild-type mice mutations that occur at A:T site is reduced by about 2-fold while the frequency of C:G mutations is increased by 2-fold there is also an increase in mutations of GYW motifs that are considered a sight of action for activation-induced cytidine deaminase

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal somatic hypermutation frequency
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit a 36% reduction in total mutation frequency in germinal center B cell compared with wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal somatic hypermutation frequency
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: strongly reduced number of A/T mutations in germinal center B cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal somatosensory cortex morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal spatial learning
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in the hidden platform water maze, mutants show no bias toward the position of the escape hidden platform, although they can swim normally to a visible platform, indicating that the absence of proximal cues impairs performance

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal spatial learning
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: on a hidden platform Morris water maze, mutants show greater latency than wild-type in finding the hidden platform by 6 days of training, despite no differences in swimming speed in a probe test (removal of platform), mutants do not spend more time in the trained quadrant or cross the trained site as seen in wild-type

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal spatial learning
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: take longer and swim a greater distance to locate the hidden platform during an 8-week Morris water maze retention, indicating impaired spatial learning

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal spatial learning

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal spatial learning
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: homozygous mice show impaired spatial learning/memory in a hidden platform swim test

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal spatial learning
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: memory retention is impaired in Morris water maze; mutants spend less time searching in target quadrant after removal of platform in probe trials on days 3 and 4 of training; after 1 additional day of training, mutants can distinguish between target and nontarget quadrants when tested 14 days after last hidden platform training day, mutants exhibit loss of spatial memory compared with wild-type and heterozygous mice; memory formation occurs, but is less stable

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal spatial learning

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal spatial learning

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal spatial learning

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal spatial reference memory

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sperm head morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: round and other misshapen sperm heads are observed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sperm head morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal sperm heads and abnormal junctions between sperm heads and midpieces are observed

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: sperm exhibit a rounder shaped head

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sperm motility

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal supraoccipital bone morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the supraoccipital is present as two lateral bony elements instead of the normal rod-like shape

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal susceptibility to autoimmune disorder
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutants develop a chronic systemic lupus-like autoimmune disease with age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal susceptibility to bacterial infection

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal susceptibility to prion infection
