OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal susceptibility to prion infection
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: altered incubation time following infection with transmissible spongiform encephalopathy

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal symmetric synapse morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show a significant reduction of vesicle number in symmetric synapses in the somatosensory cortex

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sympathetic afferent fiber morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: alteration of primary afferent terminations in the dorsal horn

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sympathetic nervous system physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: markedly attenuated sympathetic outflow after angiotensin II infusion in AdCre-treated mice relative to control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sympathetic neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: sympathetic neurons are partially protected from apoptosis induced by the withdrawal of nerve growth factor

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sympathetic neuron morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: progressive degeneration of sympathetic neurons during early postnatal development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sympathetic system morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal sympathetic innervation: adrenergic hyperinnervation in the dorsal skin

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal sympathetic system morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal sympathetic innervation; adrenergic hypoinnervation in the dorsal skin

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synapse morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: as determined by VGLUT1 (Slc17a7) staining, mice treated with tamoxifen at P15 exhibit impaired maturation of presynaptic terminals compared with control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synapse morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: marker analysis indicates an imbalance between excitatory and inhibitory synapses with higher markers of presynaptic and postsynaptic glutamatergic spines but lower levels of postsynaptic glutamatergic proteins

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synapse morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show ectopic synapses in the stratum pyramidale; numerous synaptoporin+ mossy fiber terminals are seen around CA3 pyramidal neuron somata in the stratum pyramidale and these aberrantly located terminals form synapse-like junctions containing numerous synaptoporin+ vesicles directly on the somata of CA3 pyramidal neurons or on large and branched spine-like structures emanating from the soma, often forming multiple postsynaptic densities 21 days in vitro (DIV) hippocampal neurons show an increase in the number of synaptoporin+;vGlut1+ puncta on CA3 somata indicating increased synapse formation on CA3 somata 21 DIV co-cultures of dentate gyrus neurons from mutant mice make more synaptic contacts onto wild-type CA3 somata as compared with wild-type dentate gyrus neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic bouton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: EM imaging of somatosensory cortex layers 2-3 revealed a decreased area of GABAergic boutons and decreased density of vesicles per bouton

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic bouton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: insufficient remodeling and degeneration of presynaptic membranes degeneration of presynaptic membranes at axon terminals results in appearance of tubulovesicular structures

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic bouton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice exhibit reduced radiotracer striatal uptake at 6 and 9 months of age, but not at 3 months of age and the density of striatal TH staining is decreased at 9 months of age, indicating loss of nigrostriatal dopaminergic terminals

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic bouton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Purkinje cell axon collaterals form misshapen boutons that are often displaced

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic bouton morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: large dystrophic swellings are observed in presynaptic terminals with virtual absence of postsynaptic receptor expression severe decline in the acetylcholine receptor apposition of presynaptic terminals, with ~50% of synapses showing less than half of their presynaptic area opposed by acetylcholine receptors

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic dopamine release
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: basal dopamine and amphetamine-stimulated extracellular release of dopamine is decreased in the striatum at 12, but not 6, months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic dopamine release
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice do not show a decline in the homovanillic acid/dopamine ratio from 6 to 18 months of age as is seen in wild-type mice, suggesting that the sum of dopamine metabolism and release is altered basal dopamine and amphetamine-stimulated extracellular release of dopamine is decreased in the striatum at 12, but not 6, months of age exocytotic release of dopamine and its metabolites from the vesicular pool is impaired

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic plasticity
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: robust spike time dependent potentiation lasting longer than 30 minutes resulting from pairing presynaptic with subsequent post-synaptic action potential induced layer V pyramidal neuron stimulation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic transmission
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: impaired metabotropic glutamate receptor signaling in the cerebrum

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic transmission
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show impaired basal synaptic transmission

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic vesicle clustering
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: abnormal clustering of small vesicles in spinal cords of homozygotes is observed

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic vesicle clustering
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at rest, SV numbers of visibly docked SVs per 100-nm active zone are already reduced by 40% in mutant synapses relative to controls upon stimulation (900 AP/10 Hz), SV numbers of visibly docked SVs per 100-nm active zone are reduced by 60% in mutant synapses versus only 28% in controls in mutant synapses, SVs numbers within a distance of 20 nm to the active zone are reduced to degrees similar to those of docked SVs after stimulation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic vesicle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: irregular shape in tamoxifen-treated mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic vesicle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: although stimulation with 900 AP/10 Hz increases the number of SVs with diameters >60nm in both groups, mutant resting synapses contain larger organelles more often than wild-type at rest, SVs from mutant hippocampal neurons are enlarged with diameters of ~41nm versus ~38nm in controls, and appear more heterogenous

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic vesicle morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: the number of Rab6 secretory vesicles in the growth cone of dentate gyrus neurons grown in culture is increased and many vesicles accumulate in areas of abnormal F-actin expression

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic vesicle number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: there is decreased density of synaptic terminals and synaptic vesicles in spinal cords of homozygotes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic vesicle number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tamoxifen treated mice exhibit fewer synaptic vesicles and fewer docked synaptic vesicles in asymmetric synapses compared with control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic vesicle number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show a significant reduction of vesicle number in symmetric synapses in the somatosensory cortex

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic vesicle number
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: electron micrographs of hippocampal boutons revealed that mutant resting synapses contain only ~135 SVs per um2 versus ~230 SVs per um2 in wild-type synapses after depletion of the SV pool via stimulation with 900 AP/10 Hz, mutant SV numbers are reduced to only ~47 SVs per um2 versus ~105 SVs in wild-type synapses

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptic vesicle recycling
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice display impaired recycling and acidification of synaptic vesicles in neonatal hippocampal boutons SV recycling analysis using synaptopHluorin (an exo- and endocytosis probe) revealed that weak stimulation of SV exocytosis by 100 APs at 20 Hz resulted in a slight delay in the acidification of endocytosed structures; this is increased by stimulations by 300 Aps at 10 Hz after complete depletion of the total recycling SV pool, only 46.5% of exocytosed vesicles become re-available for release relative to 94% in wild-type controls in addition, SV reformation is incomplete reaching only 70% of that in wild-type hippocampal neurons

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptonemal complex
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: synaptonemal complex structure is disturbed in pachytene and diplotene spermatocytes during late pachytene, the synaptoneal complex is thinner and the average total length of the SC is increased compared to that in wild-type pachytene and early diplotene cells

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptonemal complex
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: reduced XY synapsis in spermatocytes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synaptonemal complex
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in oocytes the length of the synaptonemal complex (SC) is significantly increased

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synovial joint capsule morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: synovial space is often dilated, containing some neutrophils and proteinaceous material

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal synovial joint capsule morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: cartilaginous nodules in joint capsules that replace menisci and support cartilage in knee joints erosion of articular surfaces in older mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal systemic arterial blood pressure
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mean arterial blood pressure response to phenylephrine is decreased by 45% mean arterial blood pressure response to norepinephrine is also decreased although to a lesser extent than seen with phenylephrine

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal systemic arterial blood pressure
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: only transient increase in mean arterial pressure (MAP) at days 1-4 of angiotensin II infusion followed by a return to normal values at days 5-13 in AdCre-treated mice, unlike the progressive increase in MAP induced by angiotensin II treatment in control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal systemic arterial blood pressure
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: after i.v. injection of lysophosphatidic acid (18:1-LPA, 1.4 mg/kg), mice show an attenuated initial hypotensive response but no differences in the LPA-induced transient hypertensive response relative to similarly treated wild-type controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal systemic arterial blood pressure
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: DEA/NO treatment causes a greater hypotensive effect than in controls

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal systemic arterial blood pressure regulation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: power spectral analysis of mean arterial pressure revealed that the power of low-frequency oscillations is not significantly increased after 14 days of angiotensin II infusion in AdCre-treated mice, unlike in control mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail bud morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail bud morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: small and irregularly shaped

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail bud morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: plastic tail in very few mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: plastic tail in very few mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail pigmentation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: unpigmented ring of epidermis, but normal dermis pigmentation, in the middle of the tail with less than 100% penetrance and fewer animals exhibiting both dorsal and ventral hypopigmentation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail pigmentation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: unpigmented ring of epidermis, but normal dermis pigmentation, in the middle of the tail with less than 100% penetrance and fewer animals exhibiting both dorsal and ventral hypopigmentation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail pigmentation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: unpigmented tail rings in 5 of 7 mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail pigmentation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: white ring around tail

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail pigmentation
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: by 12 months of age, developed a hypo-/hyper-pigmented skin phenotype on the tail

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tail position or orientation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tectum morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: Purkinje cells are present in ectopic position within the isthmic region heading toward the tectum

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tegmentum morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal telencephalon development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal telencephalon development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E17.5, mice exhibit a shift in the proportional volume of the dorsal and ventral telencephalon

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal telencephalon development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal telencephalon development

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal telencephalon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at E14.5, the hippocampus, neocortex and palaeocortex are slightly smaller than in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal telomere morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal telomere morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal temporal bone morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal temporal bone zygomatic process morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tenocyte organization is disrupted

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon cell morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tenocyte organization is disrupted

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon collagen fibril morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon collagen fibril morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: increase in the number of small diameter fibrils, abnormal fibrils and abnormally large diameter fibrils

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon collagen fibril morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: collagen fibers from tendons of 1 month old mice appear less organized and sparse as compared to controls some fibrils are large with cauliflower-like fibril contours and small diameter fibrils most abnormal fibrils are in the pericellular regions

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon collagen fibril morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: collagen fibers from tendons of 1 month old mice appear less organized and sparse as compared to controls some fibrils are large with cauliflower-like fibril contours and small diameter fibrils most abnormal fibrils are in the pericellular regions

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: differentiation and condensation of tendon progenitors is disrupted differentiation and elongation of tail tendons is disrupted organization of the endotenon and of the tendon matrix is disrupted

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: limb tendons are lost with some missing completely and others small and rudimentary the extensor digitorium communis tendon ends are the wrist the extensor digiti quinti and carpi ulnaris tendons are reduced flexor tendons are more severely affected than extensors tail tendons are missing short tendons in the trunk are reduced or disrupted while long tendons are missing intermuscular tendons including the lateral tendious stripes in the rectus abdominis muscle, subscapularis musclea at the ventral side of the scapula, and the middle tendon of the diaphragm can not be detected

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tenocyte organization is disrupted extracellular domains containing collage fiber are poorly organized

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: tenocyte organization is disrupted extracellular domains containing collage fiber are poorly organized

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal tendon stiffness
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: forelimb is locked in a dorsal flexure and mice walk on their wrists mice cannot grasp railing and tails are completely immobile

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis development
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: developmental delay starting at 2 weeks underdeveloped at 8 weeks

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis interstitial tissue morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: testes show relatively wider interstitial space

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 6-8 months of age, occasional male homozygotes display abnormal testicular morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: rete testis dilation, luminal swelling, and atrophy of the germinal epithelium of the seminiferous tubules

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: testes have several seminiferous tubules with depleted germ cells or only Sertoli cells, the characteristic Sertoli cell-only syndrome phenotype

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mice show an increase in T cell infiltration within the testis and testis shows condensed cell infiltrates and moderate shrinkage in certain tissue regions

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in 31% of homozygous mutant testes, clusters of tubules completely lack developing spermatocytes however, this abnormal testicular morphology has no impact on male fertility

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: testes show aberrant tubules

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: whole testes show significantly increased levels of sulfogalactosylglycerolipid (also known as SGG or seminolipid) at both 5 and 8 months of age C18:0/C16:0 SGG (m/z 823) and C18:1/C16:0 SGG (m/z 821), as well as C16:0 SGC (palmitoylsulfatide, m/z 778) are uniquely present in the testes, in addition to 3 other SGG species that are normally present in wild-type testes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at day 23, no sperm flagellum are detected in the testis the basement membrane underlying Sertoli cells is thinner and disrupted compared to in wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: testicular expression of autophagosome marker LC3A/B-II is significantly decreased while expression of autophagy receptor SQSTM1/p62 is significantly increased, indicating a reduction in testicular autophagy activity

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: in efferent ducts, immune cells infiltrate the epithelium and reach the lumen, blocking the transit of sperm and testicular fluid the hypoplasia and low convolution of mutant efferent ducts result in a reduction of the epithelial area involved in liquid reabsorption these phenotypes result in tissue swelling upstream the blockade due to liquid and sperm accumulation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: testicular expression levels of IFT25 (the IFT27 binding partner) and IFT81 (a component of IFT-B complex) are significantly reduced

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal testis physiology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: co-immunoprecipitation with anti-CATSPER1 antibody showed that, unlike all the other CatSper subunits examined, the protein level of CATSPER4 in the CatSper complex is significantly reduced in solubilized testis microsomes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thalamus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: axonal swelling in the posterior thalamic nucleus

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thalamus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: vacuoles began to appear in the thalamus at 2 months of age

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thalamus morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thalamus morphology
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: numerous fibrillar deposits are seen that appear to be composed of prion protein

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal third pharyngeal arch artery morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal third pharyngeal arch artery morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thrombopoiesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thrombopoiesis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thymocyte activation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thymocyte activation

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thymus cell ratio

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thymus cell ratio

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thymus corticomedullary boundary morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: abnormal thymus corticomedullary boundary morphology

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: decreased susceptibility to autoimmune diabetes

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: decreased susceptibility to autoimmune disorder
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: intranasal administration of IL-25 to wild-type mice leads to an inflammatory airway response similar to asthma with increased secretion of Th2 cytokines, mucus hypersecretion, goblet cell hyperplasia, infiltration of inflammatory cells, collagen deposition around bronchioles, and hyperesponsiveness to methacholine IL-25 intranasal treatment fails to increase levels of the Th2 cytokines CCL24, IL-5 and IL-13 in the lung as occurs in wild-type controls in response to intranasal administration of IL-25, mutant mice have no goblet cell hyperplasia or mucus hypersecretion compared to 40% of treated wild-type mice infiltration of inflammatory cells and collagen deposition around bronchioles are readily apparent in IL-25-treated mice, but not in mutant mice mutant mice in the asthma model are not hyperresponsive to methacholine treatment as are wild-type mice

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: delayed wound healing

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: increased coronary flow rate
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: isolated perfused hearts from mutant mice show no significant differences in left ventricular pressure, dP/dtmax, dP/dtmin, tissue ATP levels, phosphocreatine or myocardial oxygen consumption (MVO2) under basal conditions or after maximal beta-adrenergic  stimulation (200 nM dobutamine) relative to wild-type hearts however, mutant hearts display a ~30% increase in coronary flow under basal conditions and a >25% increase under stimulation with 50 and 200 nM dobutamine maximal coronary flow response elicited by intracoronary infusion of adenosine or as peak flow of reactive hyperemia after coronary occlusion is elevated by ~25% in mutant hearts in addition, mutant hearts display higher coronary venous PO2 (V-PO2) values: under basal conditions, mutant V-PO2 is 123 mmHg and falls to 67 and 38 mmHg at 50 and 200 nM dobutamine, respectively, whereas wild-type V-PO2  is 88 mmHg and falls to 38 and 12.5 mmHg, respectively

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: increased susceptibility to endotoxin shock

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: increased susceptibility to experimental autoimmune uveoretinitis

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: increased susceptibility to fungal infection

OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant lactating dams produce zinc-deficient milk that is lethal to all nursing pups;  however, mutant pups develop normally is foster-nursed on a wild-type dam i.p. injection of zinc glycinate into nursing pups significantly improves survival, with 70% of pups surviving on lethal milk to 16 days of age with nearly normal body weights; 80% of these survivors display normal pelage i.p. injection of glycine into nursing pups enhances survival by 30% but fails to correct the fur and weight loss phenotypes i.p. injection of copper glycinate fails to ameliorate the adverse effects of toxic milk

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: maternal effect
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: mutant females produce milk that is lethal to their progeny: offspring appears to swell, shrivel and dry up, joints stiffen, mouths remain open, and death occurs at around 6 to 8 days of age if 5-day old offspring are foster-nursed on wild-type females they do not survive; however, if offspring are fostered at 0 to 2 days of age most survive and reach reproductive maturity if wild-type 5- or 7-day old litters are fostered on mutant females, most pups survive but tend to be smaller at weaning; however, if wild-type newborns are fostered on mutant females, they die at 6-8 days of life

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: maternal effect

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: maternal effect

OntologyAnnotation.ontologyTerm.name: nephrolithiasis
OntologyAnnotation.evidence.comments.des: at 1-2 days of age, DHA crystals are found within the lumens of cortical and medullary collecting ducts of both male and female mice by 2 weeks of age, DHA crystals are detected in the lumens of proximal and distal tubules as well as collecting ducts crystals are brownish red in color, generally spherical (~10-20 um in diameter), and display numerous slender needle- to lancet-shaped structures radiating from the center of the crystal DHA crystals are also found within areas of interstitial fibrosis, surrounding atrophic cells of the S3 segment of the proximal tubule, as well as atrophic cells of the distal tubule and collecting ducts DHA crystals surrounding the atrophic tubular segments are not spherical but composed of numerous slender rod- to needle-shaped structures crystals are birefringent under polarizing optics regardless of their location tissue staining and fixation procedures drastically reduces the amount of birefringent material occasionally, several crystals aggregate within the tubular lumen, forming a much larger stone crystal formation is significantly greater in 120- to 240-day-old males relative to age-matched females
